<HEAD>Violence in Second Day of General Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-20 UPDATE with Zuniga beaten, freed, other
details. Pick up 15th graf pvs: Journalists saw ... with deletions
to trim and conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Plainclothes police stormed a building housing an opposition party office and its radio station Tuesday, setting off a rock-throwing protest by foes of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s military rule. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON>, leader and presidential candidate of the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1984, was beaten and arrested. <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON>, owner of Radio 10-FM, was released hours later. The plainclothes police and later a riot squad fired dozens of shots into the air to disperse the crowd outside the building. The brawl occurred as an anti-Noriega strike called by the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crusade </ORGANIZATION> entered its second day and appeared to be picking up support. Witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of reprisals, said plainclothes police with shotguns and pistols rushed into the Popular Action building on <ORGANIZATION> Via </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Espana </ORGANIZATION>, smashing furniture and equipment inside the radio station. Radio 10-FM was under censorship orders to play only music, but had been broadcasting news supporting the strike. An angry crowd gathered outside the building and started throwing rocks at the officers. An unidentified radio station employee was slightly injured. Leaders of the Civil Crusade, a coalition of 180 business, professional, labor, student and political groups, told a news conference Tuesday night the strike shut down 85 percent of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s economic activity. They said 90 percent of industry and construction were paralyzed. They conceded that transportation was down by only 10 percent, but said retail commerce was 40 percent of normal. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Lastra </PERSON>, a Crusade leader and a strike organizer, said `` this demonstrates the <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> people's repudiation of the dictatorship of Gen. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and the fervent desire for complete democracy. The government, through some of the news media it controls, has been calling the strike `` a complete failure,'' alleging business and transportation were functioning normally. The young security men at the radio station, dressed in jeans and T-shirts, outnumbered the protesters and broke up the demonstration after 40 minutes. The demonstrators were banging pots and pans in the streets and distributing leaflets. At least four men were punched, kicked and beaten with rubber truncheons during the melee as they were arrested and shoved into police vehicles. Two women were among those arrested on Via <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, an upper middle-class neighborhood. They were not beaten, but one was slapped on the buttocks as she was hustled into a car. At first only about 15 demonstrators from the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> were involved at the radio station building, but the crowd swelled to about 150 when residents came out on balconies or sidewalks to join in beating pans. Many people bolted for cover, however, when security agents came to screeching stops in 4-wheel-drive Toyotas. The agents jumped out and began shooting. Some residents returned to balconies from time to time, shouting `` Murderers!'' and `` Cowards!'' <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON>, leader of Popular Action, was beaten and shoved into a vehicle. The car was blocked by another vehicle and <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON>, a white-haired man of about 60, fled down the street with his torn shirt fluttering and security men in pursuit. Bystanders created interference and <PERSON> Zuniga </PERSON> dived into a car that sped away, but he was caught later. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, ousted as president last week by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, remained in hiding Tuesday. He predicted serious economic trouble. <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>'s successor, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>, accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of `` lies and defamation'' about <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, the 17,000-member military and police organization commanded by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the real power behind the civilian government. Journalists saw at least three people wounded by birdshot fired by either the plainclothes agents or soldiers who arrived later. One man was bleeding from the head, but did not seem to be seriously injured. Calm was reported elsewhere in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. By midafternoon, the strike had drastically thinned traffic and the crowds on the streets. Strike leaders said 12 Panamanian-owned banks were closed. Most international banks opened, but did comparatively little business. Only one employee and five guards occupied the main area of the large <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> branch. The scenes were similar at <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>. Some international institutions shut down, including the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>, <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>'s replacement, inaugurated a new session of the <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> with an anti-American speech. The assembly, which <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> controls, dismissed <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> last Friday. `` <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has been the victim of the most violent and terrible campaign of lies and defamation that any leader has ever received,'' <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> said. He accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and opponents of the government of `` the clear political intention of bringing ill repute on the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> Defense Forces.'' He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` wants to asphyxiate the <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> people economically.'' <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been `` a traditional enemy'' of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` They send to our country destabilizing agents who try to sow chaos in a nation that let its entrails be opened to serve the world,'' he said in a reference to the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. Panamanian officials have claimed protests at home and the indictment of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> on drug charges in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> are the work of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> conservatives who oppose the 1977 treaties under which the canal is to be turned over to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> on Dec. 31, 1999. In a videotape of <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> distributed by his associates, the former president pledged to remain in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and continue resistance to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. He said the crisis would make it impossible for <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to get new loans from abroad and described the country as `` totally bankrupt.'' <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> predicted the lack of credit would force the government to raise taxes, which he said `` will increase unemployment and social unrest.''
