<HEAD>Supreme Court Accepts First Drug Testing Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mandatory drug testing in the workplace will be studied for the first time by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in a case that involves government workers but could have an impact on private businesses as well. The justices on Monday agreed to decide whether the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, in the interest of fighting drug smuggling, may force those applying for or holding drug-enforcement jobs to be tested. The court will hear arguments in the case next fall, with a decision on the constitutionality of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration program not expected until 1989. The court also may be called upon soon to study drug and alcohol testing for federal railway workers. A federal appeals court in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> ruled on Feb. 11 that the railway testing program is unconstitutional and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said it will appeal that ruling to the high court. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Adler </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> said the high court's action on testing of government workers could influence private employers, depending on how broad the court ruling is. `` The big question is whether the court is going to determine this on a narrow, fact basis or will it attempt to articulate broad principles'' involving workers' reasonable expecations of privacy, he said. He said a narrow ruling relying on the special security needs of the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> would limit the impact in part because `` most -LRB- private -RRB- employers have shied away from random, generalized testing.'' But a sweeping endorsement of testing by the court could change that. The case before the justices is limited to whether public officials violate constitutional rights by testing those who are not suspected of using drugs. The outcome will affect tests conducted by federal, state or local governments but not by industry. Under the law, governments may not violate any rights protected by the Constitution, but private individuals or corporations have more leeway. <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> workers in sensitive jobs must provide urine samples in restroom stalls as a person overseeing the procedure waits outside the stall. The tests are conducted by an independent company hired by the service. Administration lawyers said the tests are needed to prevent agents who used drugs from being bribed or blackmailed. They said any sacrifice of personal privacy is outweighed by the need to stop drug smuggling. Government lawyers said the tests are particularly important now because the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> plans to recruit some 3,000 new employees, including many in the 18-25 age range in which use of illegal drugs is most prevalent. The Customs Service adopted the test procedure under an executive order President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed in 1986. The procedure is being challenged by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which said subjecting workers to the test is a humiliating invasion of privacy. The union welcomed the high court's intervention. Union President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tobias </PERSON> said the court's ruling will clear up `` a legal and moral morass ... and, we hope, destroy <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s plans for wholesale testing of the federal work force.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, with 30,000 employees, has adopted random testing for its workers. The program covers those in safety-related jobs such as air traffic controllers, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> pilots and workers with high-rated security clearance. The Customs Service tests, which are not administered randomly, were upheld by the New Orleans-based 5th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. The appeals court said the tests may be considered searches but do not intrude unnecessarily on the privacy rights of workers. In other actions Monday, the court: _ Agreed to decide whether states may bar a man from trying to prove he fathered the child of a woman married to someone else The `` reverse paternity'' case challenges a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> law, similar to those in many other states, that always considers the woman's husband the father _ Asked the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, in a case from <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, whether it thinks high-stakes bingo games run by Indian tribes are subject to state sales taxes _ Said it will decide whether employees of a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> intelligence agency are entitled to administrative hearings when the government fires them as security risks
