<FIRST>r w PM-OfficerStrength     03-01 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Officer Strength,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>World's Soldiers Holding up Lots of Brass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may be upset about the number of officers in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military, but the armed forces of some of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s closest allies are much more top-heavy, a survey has found. Of 11 nations surveyed by a military journal, only two had a lower ratio of admirals and generals to active-duty personnel than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Moreover, the No. 1 country among those surveyed _ <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> _ has built a military force whose ratio of generals and admirals to active-duty forces is more than three times that of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The survey was conducted by the monthly magazine `` Armed Forces Journal'' and the results summarized in its March issue, published today. The magazine said it contacted the defense ministries directly or else turned to foreign embassies in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for the information needed to make a comparison of active-duty forces. <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> possesses easily the leanest of the military establishments surveyed, with just 5 generals leading an active-duty force of 54,700, the survey found. That translates to just 0.9 generals per 10,000 active-duty personnel, the magazine reported. The next eight countries fall into a range that runs from 4 generals and admirals per 10,000 active-duty personnel to about 9 generals per 10,000. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is in this group with a ratio of 4.9 generals and admirals for every 10,000 active-duty personnel. The final two countries _ <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> _ are in a class by themselves, the magazine reported. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has 476 generals and admirals to lead its 320,000 men and women on active duty, or a ratio of 14.9 per 10,000, while <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has 141 generals and admirals for 87,254 active-duty personnel, or a ratio of 16.2 per 10,000. At the other end of the scale, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> followed <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> with 199 generals and admirals for its 495,000 on active duty, or a ratio of 4.0 generals and admirals per 10,000 troops. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has slightly more than 2.1 million men and women under arms. As of November, when the information was compiled, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had authorized 1,073 slots for generals and admirals and 1,057 of those jobs were filled. Either number produces the same ratio of roughly 4.9 per 10,000. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, complaining about what it calls `` grade creep,'' imposed the cap of 1,073 active-duty slots for generals and admirals in 1981. Lawmakers have refused ever since to raise it despite repeated Pentagon entreaties. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> also ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in its fiscal 1987 budget to begin reducing the number of lower-ranking officers in the military. The Pentagon is under orders to reduce its officer corps of colonels and captains by 6 percent by fiscal 1990 _ or more than 18,000 job slots. Before the cutting began, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> had more than 308,700 officers on active duty, or roughly one officer for every 5.9 enlisted personnel. By next September, that number must fall to 302,620, with additional cuts to follow.
</TEXT>
