<HEAD>Government, $150 Billion In Red, To Become World's Largest Charge
Card User</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government still prints money on paper for all debts public and private, but the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration says it will gladly take plastic. The Office of Management and Budget on Monday announced a new progam to increase dramatically the government's use of credit cards _ both for buying and selling. Not only will the government start accepting credit cards from the public for such items as passports and payments on college loans, but the <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> said it also hopes to develop a plan under which government officials and purchasing agents will use cards. `` Eventually, the Office of Management and Budget will be able to require that all purchases made -LRB- by the government -RRB- under $ 2,500 be by credit card,'' the <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> said in President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s `` management'' report on the federal government In fact, the report itself can be purchased by mail with VISA or <ORGANIZATION> MasterCard </ORGANIZATION>, for $ 6.50. -LRB- The president's fiscal 1989 budget costs $ 18 -RRB-. Budget Director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> news briefing he did have a few qualms about use of credit cards as an alternative to legal tender _ for a goverment that was $ 150 billion in the red last year. But, he added, by allowing citizens to repay their government debts with credit cards, `` We're collecting some of this -LRB- debt -RRB- rather than just letting it ride.'' Under the expanded program, the government is expected to process 130 million credit-card transactions annually by 1991, or $ 6.5 billion worth, said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, deputy <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> director. `` It will make us the largest credit card user in the world,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said, however, that the cards wo n't be accepted for tax payments _ at least not yet. That would require seeking legislation from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, something the administration is n't now prepared to do. However, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said the subject is being explored with the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The government for some time has accepted credit cards for specified items, including publications of the Government Printing Office. More recently, the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has accepted credit cards for duty collection at most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airports and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mint is now accepting them for coin sales. The management report also said that the government is studying, for possible future use, a system under which `` smart cards'' would be issued by the government to people who receive Social Security and other payments and benefits. `` These cards -LRB- would -RRB- have embedded on them information about the cardholder that can be accessed electronically. Potentially -LRB- the -RRB- cards could make available funds for food stamps, social security payments, or grants and control their use electronically through central computers.'' And what's to keep the government from running up large interest payments on its past-due credit card accounts, just like it has with the national debt? `` We're not going to pay -LRB- interest -RRB- because we're not going to let them go beyond 30 days,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said.
