<FIRST>r w PM-Soviet-Arms Bjt   03-01 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Arms, Bjt,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Hold to Optimistic Timetable for START Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Write</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet officials are optimistic about a strategic arms accord being reached before a summit this summer despite President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s remark last week that not enough time is left. The Soviets hope major disagreements in the Strategic Arms Reduction Talks can be settled at a March 22-23 meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> between Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and his Soviet counterpart <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. `` We remain optimistic,'' said a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> diplomat who has been involved in the negotiations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on long-range weapons. He spoke only on condition of anonymity. `` We are near the finishing line,'' he said, and `` there is still plenty of time'' before <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> meet. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> ordered their aides to draft, before that March meeting, agreements on three areas: verifying compliance, dismantling weapons, and exchanging data on the arsenals. `` These three drafts constitute the bulk of the work to be done'' on the treaty, although several major points of disagreement remain, the Soviet official said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in an interview published last Friday by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, said he did not think it possible to reach an accord before the summit, which is expected in late May or early June. `` We're not at this moment anticipating that it would be ready for signature then,' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. But he said the deal was possible before he leaves office next January. The proposed treaty would cut strategic nuclear arsenals by 35 percent to 50 percent, setting a limit of 6,000 on the overall number of warheads with ranges of more than 3,400 miles. The Soviets are balking at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demand to limit the number of warheads on land-based missiles to 3,300 and the number of warheads aboard so-called heavy missiles to 1,650, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. And the Soviets want to set a limit on numbers of sea-launched cruise missiles, above the 6,000 warhead ceiling. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have objected to such a limit, in part because it would be difficult to verify. The Soviet official repeated a remark by <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> that technology exists to detect nuclear weapons aboard naval vessels, a statement that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> experts question. `` Such things as sublimits need to be worked out at the highest political levels,'' such as the Shultz-Shevardnadze meeting in March, the official said. `` The bulk of the work, the technical details, is in the three drafts and needs to be worked out at the expert level'' before the tough political decisions, he said. The official also said the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> might drop its objections to tests in space of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Star Wars missile defense system if some limits could be negotiated beforehand. He said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would countenance some space tests as long as both sides agreed they did not violate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. The diplomat noted that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> agreed at the December summit in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to abide by the ABM treaty. But the joint communique issued at summit did not address U.S.-Soviet disagreement on the extent to which the treaty restricted space tests of weapons such as lasers and other devices that were not in use when the ABM pact was signed. The Soviets are seeking a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> response to their proposal to set limits on tests for various Star Wars components such as lasers, the official said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators have rejected such limits, saying that compliance would be impossible to verify in space.
</TEXT>
