<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AIDS-At-A-Glance     03-01 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-At-A-Glance,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, is the latest on AIDS.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>WHAT IT IS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious disease that destroys the body's immune system. It is incurable and usually fatal. Death comes from infections or cancers that the body can not fight.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>WHAT CAUSES IT</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 AIDS is caused by the human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, and is spread through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, transfusion of infected blood or blood products, or from an infected birthing mother to her baby.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>WHO GETS IT</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Chief victims of AIDS have been homosexual men and intravenous drug abusers. Health officials estimate that heterosexual contact is responsible for 4 percent of cases and that between 1 million and 1.5 million Americans have been exposed to the virus.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HOW IT'S DETECTED</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Screening for AIDS is conducted by testing blood for the presence of antibodies to the AIDS virus. The test tells only if a person has been exposed to the virus. A person with a positive test has a 20 percent to 30 percent chance of developing AIDS over a five-year period, according to the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HOW MANY HAVE IT</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 As of Feb. 22, AIDS had been diagnosed in 54,233 Americans, of whom more than half, or 30,355, have died since June 1, 1981, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>POSSIBLE TREATMENTS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Numerous types of medicines against the AIDS virus are now being studied. They are in three categories: antivirals that combat the virus; anti-infectives that treat the opportunistic infections and malignancies that occur with AIDS; and immune modulators that strengthen the immune system. An antiviral, AZT -LRB- for azidothymidine -RRB-, has received <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> approval and early results show it is effective in halting progress of the AIDS virus. At least 16 other antivirals are in some stage of development and testing. Scientists also are searching for a vaccine against the virus, but this research is in early stages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0012 </DOCNO>
