<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressional critic of federal officials' flying in style on taxpayer-supplied executive aircraft says he's unhappy with an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> move to clip the wings of the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., expressed his displeasure Monday after the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> told him the corps had been been stripped of day-to-day control of three aircraft that have been called wasteful by <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and congressional auditors <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ambrose </PERSON>, who stepped down Friday as undersecretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, said he ordered the executive aircraft placed in a central pool, forcing the corps brass to compete against other <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> commanders for their use. `` The pooled operation, we anticipate, will yield economies,'' <PERSON> Ambrose </PERSON> told <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>'s Government Operations subcommittee on environment, energy and natural resources. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Elvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Heiberg </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, the three-star chief of engineers, told the hearing that `` I concur with the decision made by my boss. ... We'll have to compete.'' Last summer, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the corps had been using the aircraft not for emergencies such as floods but for routine and ceremonial matters, many of them overseas trips on which leaders were accompanied improperly by spouses. <PERSON> Ambrose </PERSON> said that before they can use any of the aircraft, <PERSON> Heiberg </PERSON> and other corps leaders will have to get flight-by-flight permission from the director of <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> staff in the Pentagon. <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> said he was displeased because the director of staff has been responsible for authorizing travel by corps spouses, who <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> regulations say must have an `` unquestionable official'' role in a government-financed trip. `` Unless he does a better job than he has done with spouse travel, this is n't going to be much of a safeguard,'' <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Heiberg </PERSON> and other corps officials have defended their use of the aircraft on grounds that they are more efficient than commercial flights. <PERSON> Ambrose </PERSON>'s action partially settled an in-Army fight between the corps and the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> auditors, who said last year that tax dollars could be saved by selling the planes and having corps officials use commercial or charter flights. <PERSON> Ambrose </PERSON> said the Army would decide later this year whether to sell the aircraft, including Castle I, the 14-passenger jet that has been used to ferry key members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on trips to visit water projects around the nation. Before the aircraft can be sold, however, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will have to repeal a law forbidding such a sale. The prohibition was quietly enacted in December at the behest of one of those flyers, Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, D-Ala., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee that handles corps funding <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON> said he disagreed with the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> auditors and with similar findings made over the years by the congressional <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. `` All three planes are needed,'' <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON> said. `` They do their best work when there's floods and emergencies.''
