<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Emmett </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>'s handling of the 1985 vote fraud trial of three <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> civil rights activists has come under fire during a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hearing on his nomination to the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Stavis </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, told the panel Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> displayed `` an intolerance toward and a failure to respect'' a black lawyer involved in the trial and issued rulings that raised questions about his sensitivity to racial issues. <PERSON> Stavis </PERSON>' testimony marked the second time that the vote fraud trial has been used as the basis for opposing one of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s judicial nominees. The trial, which civil rights groups charged was part of an effort by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to intimidate black voters in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, ended in innocent verdicts for all three activists. It then became the focal point of a 1986 campaign by civil rights groups against <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s nomination of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney Jefferson B. Sessions III to a federal judgeship in south <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. Sessions, who was prosecutor at the vote fraud trial, was rejected by the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, marking the first time that one of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s judicial nominees has been voted down in committee. While the Sessions nomination drew opposition from a host of civil rights groups, <PERSON> Stavis </PERSON> was the only witness Monday who testified in opposition to <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION>. The committee did not vote on the nomination, but Sen. <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON>, D-Ala., who presided at the hearing, predicted that <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> would win <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation within a month <PERSON> Stavis </PERSON> criticized <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>'s decision during the 1985 trial to bring criminal contempt of court charges against <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> lawyer who represented one of the activists. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> had ruled that <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s questioning of a witness violated his order barring defense attorneys from raising the issue of selective prosecution. That contempt ruling later was reversed by the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stavis </PERSON>, who represented <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that `` there was absolutely no foundation'' for the contempt charge. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> acknowledged Monday that the appeals court had `` fairly concluded'' that he had been wrong to cite <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> for contempt. `` They educated me on the law of criminal contempt,'' he said. <PERSON> Stavis </PERSON> also charged that <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> had shown a lack of racial sensivitity by refusing to delay the trial for two weeks so the jury could be selected from a jury pool drawn from the <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, area, which had a much larger percentage of blacks than did the jury pool drawn from the Mobile, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, area. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> declined during the hearing to respond specifically to <PERSON> Stavis </PERSON>' testimony about the jury selection issue. But he told reporters afterwards that racial considerations played no part in his handling of the case.
