<HEAD>T-Bills Mixed In Latest Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities were mixed in the latest auction with three-month bills dropping to the lowest level since November while rates on six-month bills edged up. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 6.4 billion in three-month bills Monday at an average discount rate of 5.62 percent, down from 5.64 percent last week. Another $ 6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.86 percent, up from 5.83 percent last week. The rates on three-month bills were the lowest since 5.49 percent on Nov. 30 while the six-month bills were the highest since they averaged 6.03 percent on Feb. 16. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 5.78 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,857.90 and 6.12 percent for a six-month bill selling for $ 9,703.70. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, dropped to 6.63 percent last week, down from 6.70 percent the previous week.
