</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s sergeant at arms _ <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Giugni </PERSON> _ became an instant celebrity last week when he followed orders and arrested Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore. <PERSON> Giugni </PERSON>'s posse had <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> carried onto the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor to constitute a quorum so consideration could continue of a controversial campaign financing act, then besieged by a filibuster It was not the first time a senate sergeant of arms has been the focus of attention by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the press. On Feb. 7, 1935, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted to fire Sergeant at Arms <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>'s offense: The 72-year-old former journalist had written a magazine article entitled `` Over the Hill to Demagoguery'' which he had thought would be published after he left office. But the publication date was moved up and when the article appeared it began with these words: `` Contrary, perhaps, to the popular belief, there are not many crooks in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>; that is out and out grafters, or those who are willing to be such. `` There are not many senators or representatives who sell their votes for money, and it is pretty well known who those few are. `` But there are many demagogues.'' Senate Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, who recounted the incident on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor recently, said the article probably would have been ignored had it been written by a journalist. `` But for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s sergeant at arms it was an entirely different matter,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` So the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted him out of office, less than a month before his term would have ended.''
