<HEAD>International Study Shows American Students Far Behind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Students in most other countries are far better educated in science than are American students, according to an international study that one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said emphasizes `` the troubled state of science education in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' In a report released Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students at three different grade levels all scored well behind those from most other nations, with some American 14-year-olds scoring at the level of the `` scientifically illiterate.'' `` For a technologically advanced country, it would appear that -LRB- in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> -RRB- a re-examination of how science is presented and studied is required,'' said the study, which was conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evaluation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Achievement </ORGANIZATION>, an association of research centers. <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, said of the study: `` These findings emphasize again the troubled state of science education in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. ... <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future as a world technological and economic leader and the quality of life we enjoy depend on confronting the real problems in science education with vigor, determination and a sense of urgency.'' The study was conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evaluation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Achievement </ORGANIZATION>, an association of research centers. Early findings, which compared the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> only with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and with partial findings from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, were reported by The Associated Press in September. The comparative study was based on tests administered to 204,308 students at 7,581 schools in 24 countries between 1983 and 1986. The tests were given at three academic levels: near the end of primary grades, at about age 10; at grades eight and nine, about age 14; and in the final year of high school. Among 10-year-olds, students in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> scored around 15.4 out of 24 possible correct answers. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students scored just below the middle of the scale at 13.2. Among 14-year-olds, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> scored at the top, while Americans ranked third from last with a mean score of 16.5 out of 30 possible correct answers. The lowest-scoring quarter of this age group, the report said, `` were scientifically illiterate'' with their test scores `` at chance level.'' Tests for the high school seniors were given only to those specializing in science subjects. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> scored highest, with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> students receiving among the lowest marks. In an analysis of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> results, the report said: `` The achievement of advanced science students in biology, chemistry and physics is low. The biology results are especially low.'' The study said that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, along with <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, has `` many poor scoring schools and it would seem likely that the school authorities would have grounds for concern.'' Secretary of Education <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, responding to a report of the study, said it supports an assessment on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> education that his department released last week. `` Now comes this international report card showing that compared to students in other countries, American elementary and high school students are not just in a ` dead stall,' they're doing even worse,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` They're in reverse and going downhill.'' The international study also compared the difference in science achievement based on gender. In grades five and nine, boys scored higher than girls in all countries. For grade 12, boys outperformed girls in biology, chemistry and physics, except in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, where girls had top marks in biology.
