<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Owens-Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has acquired virtually all outstanding shares of <ORGANIZATION> Brockway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stock to the tune of about $ 740 million and is on the verge of creating the nation's largest glass container company, offcials say. Monday's move followed a decision by the government against appealing a court decision in favor of the merger. <ORGANIZATION> Owens-Illinois </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the company bought 12,337,630 shares of common <PERSON> Brockway </PERSON> stock, 98.7 percent of the outstanding shares. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the actual merger will likely occur in a couple of weeks, at which time the remaining shares will be purchased. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanigan </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Owens-Illinois </ORGANIZATION>, said the merger will make the combined operations and the glass container industry `` significantly more competitive with can, plastic and other materials in the worldwide packaging business.'' <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ticknor </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, declined to specify why the agency decided against appealing a decision by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> that, in effect, paving the way for the merger. However, Ms. <PERSON> Ticknor </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> has scheduled administrative hearings on potential anticompetitive effects of the merger. And she said <ORGANIZATION> Owens-Illinois </ORGANIZATION> could be ordered to divest itself of <PERSON> Brockway </PERSON> holdings if the agency determines that the merger violates antitrust laws. The <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, based <ORGANIZATION> Owens-Illinois </ORGANIZATION> proposed to buy <PERSON> Brockway </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, last September for $ 60 a share. The merger will make the combined company the nation's largest manufacturer of glass containers, which are used in packaging foods and beverages. The largest producer of glass containers has been <ORGANIZATION> Anchor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Glass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Container </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Owens-Illinois </ORGANIZATION> officials have said the only weapon the glass container industry has against plastics and metal packaging producers is competitive pricing and the merger with <PERSON> Brockway </PERSON> is designed to increase productivity and lower costs. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> had attempted in court to block the merger, saying it might violate antitrust laws by substantially reducing competition and creating the conditions for price discrimination. However, last month <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hens </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> denied the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION>'s request for a preliminary injunction on the basis that the agency had failed to prove the deal would harm competition. And last Friday, the appeals court sided with Judge <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, saying that the agency had failed to make its case.
