<HEAD>Jackson Showing in Maine Seen as Breakthrough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s surprise second-place finish in the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Democraatic caucuses was a `` breakthrough,'' proving conclusively that he has broadened his appeal, his backers say. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> reaped 28 percent of the vote in the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> contest on Sunday, on the heels of respectable showings in three other states which, like <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, all have voting age black populations of 1 percent or less. The <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> results came after he spent just $ 13,000 in the state and campaigned there only two days. The well-funded winner, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, is well known to <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> voters as governor of nearby <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, and he captured 42 percent. `` It shows that we can get votes in any part of the country,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Monday in <LOCATION> Pembroke </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> `` It shows we have the broadest base ... and our campaign has the strongest appeal.'' `` The <ORGANIZATION> Rainbow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> is coming alive,'' he added, invoking the name he has given to his target constituency of all minority groups and the economically oppressed. Political consultant <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, an informal <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> adviser, called <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> `` the most significant breakthrough state for him so far.'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckel </PERSON>, a top political strategist for <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>'s 1984 presidential bid, said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s performance is `` a sign of a growing movement among non-black supporters of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, and for people to try to ignore it, they're making a great mistake.'' In <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampsh