 that this is a significant guy in the party.'' Political analyst <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, however, questioned whether <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s white votes are really the downtrodden whom he has targeted. He cited exit polls from <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> showing a good portion of his votes came from upscale, well-educated liberals, `` the radical chic.'' But he also noted that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has a strong message that appeals to many Democrats. `` There is no other candidate in the race who really stands for the old politics ... what I would call Democratic fundamentalism,'' as espoused by the late Sen. <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>. <PERSON> Beckel </PERSON> said people `` consistently underestimate'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` He's the most charismatic candidate in the field. He's got a message that's concise, that does not change from place to place.'' <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Democratic chairman <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Barton </PERSON> said timing was a key for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s successful appearance at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Orono </LOCATION> on Feb. 11, just after <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s caucuses and just before the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> primary, was `` just the right time ... when <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Democrats were starting to lock in,'' he said. <PERSON> Barton </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> probably also picked up about 5 percentage points from people who defected from the flagging campaigns of <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>.
