<HEAD>Meetings and Phone Calls, And Not Much Time For
Impeachment-Watching</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's a far cry from the Capitol, but it's got most of the comforts of home Impeached Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> still goes to work early and stays late. But his office-in-exile is in a house he once lived in, across an alley from a hay barn in the far reaches of this <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> suburb. His days are filled with meetings and phone calls, he says, leaving not much time to follow his televised impeachment trial, which opened Monday in the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` No, I did n't watch,'' <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> said. `` I've been busy. I've got a lot to do.'' <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> met with supporters and attended a meeting downtown. He took time to hold a news conference in what used to be a sunken living room. But he did n't hang on every vote in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which on Monday decided the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s impeachment document was sufficient for trial. `` Frankly, I have n't tracked the vote and I have n't tried to interpret anything,'' he said. His paid staff of five worked on one side of the 7,000-square-foot ranch-style house while volunteers worked on the other side to raise money for the governor's legal defense and recall election campaign. Plans were being readied for a Wednesday night rally. Some 300 phone calls come in each day, spokesman <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. The house was converted into office space before <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was impeached Feb. 5 and replaced by acting Gov. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, the former secretary of state. Outside, a simple sign identifies the `` Governor <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> Headquarters,'' and adds, `` Office Space Available. Inquire Within.'' The building sits between a farm full of sheep, chickens and roosters, and a Mormon church. Police sometimes guard the front door, and a security system is in place. Monday's proceedings made the switchboard light up, a receptionist said, including a series of obscene phone calls. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> said he wo n't venture downtown to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> unless it's necessary `` When my attorney tells me I should be there, I'll be there,'' he said. He said he was disappointed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> chose not to grant requests for a delay in the trial since his new chief counsel has been on the case less than a week, but was confident in his defense. `` We have no choice. We have a time to get ready by,'' he said. `` I feel confident we'll be able to get our case out and I think we'll be successful,'' the governor said. `` If the decision is made on the evidence, I expect to get 29 votes.'' One member of the 30-member chamber is absent from the trial because of illness. A two-thirds vote is needed to convict <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was impeached on allegations of concealing a $ 350,000 campaign loan, misusing $ 80,000 from a special fund and attempting to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat involving a state official. He also has been indicted in state district court on six felony counts involving the $ 350,000 loan, which amounted to about a third of his campaign funds, and faces a criminal trial March 22. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> also faces a recall election May 17.
