re not,'' <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON> said in a recent <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> radio interview `` But the fact still remains that there is an enormous military potential on the other side of the Eastern border.'' Polls indicate a more relaxed attitude among West Europeans to the neighboring Communist giant under the urbane <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. A survey by <PERSON> Datagroep </PERSON> of <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> among 6,064 people in nine <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> countries last spring indicated that nearly two-thirds thought that public views of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had recently grown warmer. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who has been among <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s most outspoken admirers in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, appears to have helped the shift in public opinion. After her <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> visit last spring a Gallup sounding reported that 58 percent of Britons thought the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` really wanted to be friendly with the West.'' Just 33 percent thought Soviet advances should be treated `` with the greatest suspicion.'' <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Economist weekly commented: `` Could that in part be a result of the flattering attentions the prime minister has been happy to receive from Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>?''
