<HEAD>Gephardt Is Main Target In One Of Campaign's Liveliest Debates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The debate-a-day Democratic presidential field was scattered across the Super Tuesday landscape today after a forum in which Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> was singled out for attacks on his trade policy, tax vote and the contributions he has taken from special interests. In one of the liveliest debates of the campaign, the Democrats spelled out differences on trade, taxes and foreign debt with bare-knuckled zest, sparing not even the moderator who was chided by <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> for asking `` a race-based question.'' After the third Democratic debate in as many days, the contenders were campaigning in states that will hold primaries or caucuses on March 8, the most delegate-rich day in the history of presidential politics. Shortly after Monday's debate ended, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> flew South to meet with former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and receive the endorsement of two former governors of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> was campaigning in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>; Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, former <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> in the state of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> took heat for his acceptance of campaign contributions from political action committees, for his vote for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1981 tax cut and for his trade poli