answer the question.'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> passed up the debate, which was held on the campus of the College of <PERSON> William </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> and was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> officials who banded together out of concern over what they saw as the party's leftward drift and the failure of its presidential candidates to appeal to voters in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and West One of the most dramatic exchanges took place when moderator <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> correspondent of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> MacNeil-Lehrer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hour </ORGANIZATION>, asked <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> why he had n't been `` nearly as vocal talking about the differences between yourself and Rev. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Would that be because you do n't want to offend his black supporters?'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> replied that `` the reason is he does n't have a record to talk about in public life.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> went on to say he had disagreed with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> on issues such as defense spending. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was bristling and he turned to <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> and said: `` That is a race-based question. ... `` I am a bona fide Democrat. I have registered more Democratic voters than anyone on this stage. I am the reason why some Democrats are on this stage, because of that work. ... My race is self-evident and my leadership is obvious.''
