<HEAD>Inflation Erodes the Impact of Fines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The penalties for violating government safety laws has not kept up with inflation and has pulled the enforcement teeth from many of the laws by reducing the impact of fines, according to a coalition of consumer groups. Penalties for violating various health and safety laws have remained essentially unchanged over the years, while inflation has reduced the value of the amounts involved, the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> said Monday in a report. `` Letting civil penalties be eroded by inflation operates as if there were a built-in depreciation schedule in our key health and safety statutes,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldman </PERSON> of the group <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement released with the study. As one example the study cited the Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970 retains its original penalties of $ 1,000 per violation and $ 10,000 for failure to provide a safe workplace. To keep place with inflation these would have to increase to $ 2,970 and $ 29,700, the report said.
