<HEAD>Dollar And Stocks Close Higher In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Late-afternoon dollar purchases by speculators pushed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency higher in uninspired <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> trading today, while stock prices rose in unusually heavy trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, dealers said. The dollar opened at 128.45 yen, up 0.33 yen from Monday's close, following gains on overseas markets It then edged up in afternoon trading to close the day at 128.63 yen, up 0.51 yen. Spot volume totaled a moderate $ 4.7 billion. Despite the large day-to-day rise in the dollar's value, traders said there was little news that was influencing trading in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. `` The actual range in trading during the day was n't very great, only about 0.2 yen,'' said a trader at a <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> commercial bank who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` Most of the increase was due to speculators trying to cover dollar-short positions in the late afternoon.'' The 225-share Nikkei Stock Average, which ended 13 consecutive days of gains with a decline of 42.06 points Monday, rose 193.09 points, or 0.8 percent, to finish the day at 25,435.90. Stocks in many sectors rose, with trading in the market's first section an exceptionally heavy 1.6 billion shares, the highest so far this year. The second-section index also rose, gaining 1.56 points to hit an all-time high of 2,927.31. Dealers said stocks were spurred upward by a surge on Wall Street on Monday that pushed the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average up 48.41 points to 2,071.61, its highest level since last year's market crash But they said the market received additional impetus from bullishness resulting from favorable Japanese economic trends. `` Lately, the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market has been acting more independently of Wall Street,'' said <PERSON> Michio </PERSON> <PERSON> Katsumata </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest brokerage `` Stocks in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> are being buoyed by predictions of higher Japanese corporate profits in March. Also, the large amount of capital in circulation is boosting the market, resulting in an excess of buy orders over sell orders.'' The announcement today that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s unemployment rate in January rose 0.1 percent from December had little impact on the market, traders said. January's 2.7 percent rate was down from 3.0 percent for the same month last year.
