<HEAD>Survey Finds Large Increase in U.S. Students Studying Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A rapidly growing number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> college students are studying abroad, especially in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, according to a new study. In 1985-86, 48,483 students took courses for academic credit in foreign schools, according to latest figures released Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest higher education exchange agency. In 1982-83, the most recent previous study, 27,145 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students studied abroad, said <PERSON> Edrice </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IIE </ORGANIZATION>'s senior publications editor. The survey was conducted by mail last year to 2,896 accredited <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> colleges and universities, of which 1,898 reported students earning academic credit for study abroad. The study did not explain the rise in popularity of foreign study. But administrators on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> college campuses said that at least som students may be finding that study overseas is economical compared with the more expensive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> schools where tuitions have been soaring throughout the 1980s. At <ORGANIZATION> Beaver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Glenside </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, a school noted for study-abroad programs that students from some 225 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> colleges participate in, president <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Landman </PERSON> said she believed the increase stemmed from `` an increasing sensitivity among students to foreign study, not only to help their careers, but especially in the last year or two, to the kinds of understandings we as world citizens must bring to our lives.'' The school is sending over 1,700 students from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> campuses to study in the British <LOCATION> Isles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> this year, <PERSON> Landman </PERSON> said, compared with about 750 students in 1980-81. At <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where the numbers of students in overseas programs have risen at least 10 percent in that period, <PERSON> Orville </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, assistant dean of international programs said that as more students have traveled during their high school years, the thought of studying overseas is no longer as strange or frightening. The survey found that 76.8 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students abroad were studying in Western European countries. The most popular single country, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, attracted 29.3 percent of all students studying abroad, followed by <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> with 13.7 percent, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> with 8.8 percent, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> 7.8 percent, and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> 6.1 percent. <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> attracted 7 percent, with smaller percentages studying in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Nearly 90 percent of the students were in programs sponsored by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> colleges and universities, the survey found. The most popular field of study was liberal arts, with 18.2 percent, followed by foreign language with 16.7 percent. Almost two-thirds, or 63.8 percent, of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students abroad were female, according to the report.
