<HEAD>Tensions Simmer Anew At Dartmouth Over Conservative Paper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>'s Afro-American Society planned more protests this week after a black professor came under renewed attack from a conservative student newspaper The dispute between The <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> and music Professor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> threatened to reignite tensions that shattered the <ORGANIZATION> Ivy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> campus after a January 1986 sledgehammer attack by Review members on anti-apartheid shanties on the college green. The independent weekly's editor, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>, who also was involved in the shanty attack, faces college disciplinary charges with three other Review members stemming from a confrontation with <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> last week after the paper printed a cover story questioning his competence. Cole had sued the newspaper for libel for a January 1983 article that said he `` looks like a used Brillo pad'' and called his music course `` the most outrageous'' on campus. Cole dropped the suit in 1985 and received no damages. He and the newspaper each claimed vindication. A member of the <ORGANIZATION> Afro-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, sophomore <PERSON> Kimberly </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, said Monday the newspaper's new attacks were `` obviously racially motivated.'' About 250 students held a rally Monday in front of the college administration building, and <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said the Afro-American Society planned to start a boycott today of <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION> businesses that advertise in the Review. The group also planned a march down <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Fraternity Row'' Wednesday night and a rally with students from other area colleges Thursday. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said members of Afro-American Society also met twice Monday with <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Freedman </PERSON> to detail allegations of other recent racial incidents on campus. In its cover story two weeks ago, the Review revived charges that <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> is incompetent and printed excerpts from a transcript of one of his classes that week. The story also leveled criticisms at an English professor who is white. <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> said both stories originated from complaints to the newspaper by students in the classes. <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> denied the article was racially motivated and said the Review is the victim of a `` witch hunt'' as it tries to root out incompetence at <LOCATION> Dartmouth </LOCATION>. He said he and two Review colleagues, with a fourth as an observer, approached <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> after his class Thursday to advise him that he could publish an unedited response in the newspaper, but also to seek his explanation for remarks about the Review he allegedly made during a class. <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> said an `` altercation'' ensued. The next day, the Review published on its cover a picture of Cole during the incident and a story about it. <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Huppe </PERSON> said <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> and the other three students face college charges of disorderly conduct, harassment and violation of the right to privacy because of the confrontation. `` To have four students exercise their will over the institution, we're not going to let four students do that,'' said <PERSON> Huppe </PERSON>. The four are scheduled to appear before a disciplinary board next Tuesday. Cole could not be reached for comment. He did not return a message left on his telephone answering machine Monday night. <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> was among a dozen students involved in a pre-dawn sledgehammer attack on symbolic anti-apartheid shanties set up by student protesters in January 1986. After a series of hearings and appeals, he was sentenced to serve 180 hours of community service. The shanty attack sparked sit-ins and protests that continued all semester and led to a one-day moratorium on classes for discussions of racism.
