<HEAD>National Association Drug Committee Chief Says War on Drugs
Failing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's war on drugs has been little more than a skirmish that failed to stem the movement of drugs across <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> borders, says the head of a task force of prosecutors. `` The federal government, despite all the talk, has failed to stop the drug trafficking across the borders,'' State's Attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attorney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s annual conference Monday `` And it's increasing each year. It's not going down.'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, head of the association's <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> border patrols capture only 15 percent of the illegal drugs coming into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, while marijuana and cocaine worth $ 130 billion a year is entering from Latin American countries. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> also said the federal government is not properly funding local efforts to prosecute criminals as promised when the war on drugs was declared. `` I do n't think it's a war on drugs. I think it's only been skirmishes,'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said. `` They do n't really have a national policy. That's where it fails.'' When the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration first attacked drug use in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, it set aside $ 225 million to help local prosecutors, who handle at least 95 percent of the drug cases in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said. But this year funding was cut to $ 70 million, although the drug problem is getting worse and more violent, he said. `` The federal government should put its money where its mouth is,'' said <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, the son of the late <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>. `` We local prosecutors are on the offensive and we need federal help. `` The drug people are going to corrupt this country more and more. And you're going to see more violence. You're just seeing the beginning.'' The association delegates approved four resolutions dealing with drug enforcement, including one urging federal funding for local anti-drug programs to be reinstated to `` adequate levels.'' They called for combining state and federal efforts to block the importation of illegal drugs into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. A third resolution asked the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to channel its efforts toward helping `` prevent drug dealers from enjoying the profits of their illegal activity.'' The association also asked for a federal program to help fund the construction of county and state prisons to house the increased number of convicted drug offenders. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said the idea of educating the public to `` just say no'' has gone far enough and the concentration should be placed on people who have said yes to drugs for years. `` I'm not a social worker and I'm not a teacher,'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said. `` I'm a prosecutor.''
