<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> appealed today to communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to take part in the 1988 Olympic Games and pledged not to impose any conditions on the north's participation. `` There is no condition. ... We will welcome you, the breathren in the north, more than anyone else as the same countrymen and brothers,'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> told an audience of 4,000 people at the Sejong cultural center in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> made the strongest appeal in recent months to the north to take part in the Games, speaking during celebrations of Samil Day, a national holiday commemorating a 1919 uprising against Japanese rule. He also appealed for national reconciliation in the south. `` Today, we recall our breathren ... who rose up with bare fists against the Japanese imperialist colonial rule,'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> said. Less than one mile away, police today kicked and punched dissidents and dragged away dozens of them after breaking up an anti-government protest in <LOCATION> Pagoda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, where the 1919 uprising took place. Prominent dissident leaders were among those detained. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> hinted at his willingness to meet with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> leaders by saying he was ready to deal with anybody. He repeated that the south would seek to establish relations with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s main allies, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` I will meet with anyone, anytime and anywhere and will not hesitate to open that road however rugged it might be,'' he said. The new president, formally sworn in Feb. 25, said the Olympic Games could help speed reunification of the divided <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is demanding to co-host the Olympic Games and says it will boycott the Games if its request is denied. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> have rejected the demand, but said the north could stage five events if it takes part in the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> events. The two nations have existed since 1948 and fought the bloody Korean War from 1950 to 1953. The bitter rivals have clashed repeatedly over the years. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> also appealed to the South Korean opposition to work with his government in ending decades of authoritarian rule and introducing full democracy. `` The curtain has been raised for the era of national self-esteem in which democracy will blossom,'' he said. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, a former general, won the first democratic presidential elections in 16 years last December with 36.6 percent of the vote after rival opposition candidates split the opposition vote. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> campaigned on the platform that he alone could ensure democracy and stability. About 150 dissidents staged a demonstration today in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>'s Pagoda Park to denounce <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> and demand the immediate release of all political prisoners Protesters waved placards, shouted slogans and applauded speeches as hundreds of onlookers watched. `` Down with the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> government!'' and `` Release all the political prisoners!,'' the protesters shouted. Scuffles began when plainclothes police tried to detain some protesters and other dissidents protested. A column of about 100 police suddenly charged into the protest, kicking and punching people to the ground and chasing others. Police hauled away about 40 dissidents, some of whom were badly beaten. Police also hit a number of press photographers covering the demonstration. The Rev. Moon Ikhwan and several other prominent dissident leaders were taken away by police. Some of those detained included radicals released from prison Saturday as part of a government amnesty. Opposition leaders rejected the amnesty as insufficient and have demanded the release of all political prisoners. The government says only dissidents guilty of violent crime or subversion remain in jail.
