 <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is trying to undermine U.N.-sponsored <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> peace talks, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s ambassador to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> charged today. The ambassador, <PERSON> Mohamadulah </PERSON> <PERSON> Subhani </PERSON> <PERSON> Safi </PERSON>, made the comment on the eve of a new round of negotiations, telling a news conference that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> `` does n't want peace'' for its Afghan neighbors. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which represents the Afghan guerrillas in the talks that resume in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on Wednesday, is trying to `` raise issues that have no relevance to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>,'' he charged. <PERSON> Safi </PERSON> complained about <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s demand that any accord signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> that would facilitate a withdrawal of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> be linked to the formation of a transitional, coalition government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Without such an interim government, unending civil strife would follow a Soviet pullout, Pakistani diplomats have argued. But <PERSON> Safi </PERSON> said the composition of the Afghan government can not be dictated by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> or any outside power. His comments were echoed in an article in Pravda, the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily, which said <LOCATION> Pakistani </LOCATION> leaders have `` apparently forgotten their previous statements that the presence of the Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> was the sole obstacle in the way toward resolving the Afghan problem.'' Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has pledged _ if peace talks are successful _ to begin withdrawing an estimated 115,000 troops from its e