<HEAD>U.N. Human Rights Commission Condemns South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Denouncing what it called <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s `` escalation of acts of terrorism'' against blacks, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has renewed its call for mandatory sanctions against the white-led nation The 43-country panel, at its annual meeting Monday, urged that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> be economically isolated. It said children were increasingly being targeted for repression. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> dissented in the 36-3 vote. <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> abstained. The resolution accuses <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> of continuing `` gross and cruel violations of human rights'' under apartheid. It calls for the immediate release of <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, imprisoned leader of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement and freedom for all political prisoners in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` Massacres and daily killings of defenseless men, women and children have become the order of the day,'' the resolution says. It says human rights violations have risen under a government-imposed state of emergency that went into effect in June 1986, and urges the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to impose mandatory sanctions on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Separately, the commission asked all governments to immediately cut trade, manufactur