<HEAD>Historical Play Under Fire In Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's new policy of glasnost will suffer if theaters are barred from performing a play criticized for its portrayal of Soviet history, eight leading theater figures said. The Soviet people have gotten glasnost through suffering and `` that's why any attempts to turn the process backwards ... arouse deepest concern,'' said the three actors, three producers and two playwrights in a letter published Monday in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, or more openness on some issues, has led to greater artistic freedom. Lately, Soviet artists have produced plays on subjects they would not have touched before. The eight accused several critics of trying to block the staging of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatrov </PERSON>'s play `` Onward _ Onward _ Onward'' by `` pinning political labels'' on its author. Earlier this month, three historians told Pravda the play compared Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> to <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> _ denounced after his death as a dictator _ and portrayed Soviet history in a negative way. The eight said the timing of the criticism indicated it was aimed at dissuading theaters from booking the play. `` It is not by chance that in the provinces they manage to hear this voice. We have information at the Union of Theater Workers that this new play, devoted to <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, already was banned in some towns,'' the eight wrote. <PERSON> Shatrov </PERSON>'s new work takes the form of a debate among Bolsheviks and their opponents as they look back on Soviet history since the 1917 revolution that brought the Communists to power. The historians accused <PERSON> Shatrov </PERSON> of using <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> as a conduit for his own ideas and treating the Bolshevik revolution as an accident. In their letter, the eight said <PERSON> Shatrov </PERSON> has written about <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> for 30 years and his plays have been well received. <PERSON> Shatrov </PERSON>'s new play was published in January in the literary magazine <LOCATION> Znamya </LOCATION> and is scheduled to be performed in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> this spring. In the play, <PERSON> Shatrov </PERSON> makes <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> answer for his purges in which millions of people perished, but in one scene <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> accepts blame for not making certain <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> could not gain power after <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s death in 1924 In the closing scene, <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> are on stage. The desire is expressed for <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> to leave, but he will not. `` Yes, we do want <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> to leave, not only the stage, but our lives,'' the eight said in the letter. `` We want his methods to vanish, his ` morality,' his ways to solve disputes, in particular in art. But unfortunately, the heritage of the past can not be overcome by pronouncements.'' `` We are not going to defend the play or attack it,'' they added. `` It has n't been staged yet and a play without being staged is a soul without a body. We are concerned with other things.'' In a seven-paragraph comment on the letter, <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> said it would not take sides. `` Pravda's point of view is well known,'' it said. `` It has always been against anybody's monopoly for truth and against the position ` There is my opinion and there is a wrong opinion'.''
