<HEAD>Barge Rolled Upright, More Oil Leaks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANACORTES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a month of preparation, it took only 17 minutes to roll over an upside-down oil barge that had been raised from the bottom of <LOCATION> Guemes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Channel </LOCATION> and partially unloaded. A floating sheen of oil reached the shore of <LOCATION> Shannon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> before and during the rollover Monday in a release estimated at 300 gallons to 500 gallons of a light grade of oil. Much of it was sopped up with absorbent materials. `` I'm relieved, because it eliminates an ecological time bomb,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Eldo </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLong </PERSON>. The 176-foot barge sank Jan. 31 in 130 feet of water four miles west of <LOCATION> Anacortes </LOCATION>. It was raised from the bottom Sunday by two giant derricks. The site is about 75 miles north of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s inner coast in an area of Dungeness crabs, salmon farms, bottom fish and other saltwater life Officials had said that 70,000 gallons of oil escaped from the barge when it sank, and another 344,000 gallons was still on the barge when the lifting operation began Sunday. Roughly 92,610 gallons of oil was pumped out Sunday night and Monday. More oil was to be pumped out of the barge until it was stable enough to be towed to port. Some oil has been detected in kelp beds and in bottom-dwelling sea cucumbers, and at least one bird has died. The barge, operated by Olympic Tug and <ORGANIZATION> Barge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, was being towed from an oil refinery at <LOCATION> Anacortes </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> when it sank.
