<HEAD>Carter: Bitterness Would Only Give Prosecution Another Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former boxer <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> `` Hurricane'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, breaking a 12-year silence after finally winning his long battle for freedom, says he was sentenced to `` a life of living death'' but is not bitter. `` For 20 years, I was considered a danger to society, a scourge upon humanity. I was locked away in an iron cage for not one, but three lifetimes,'' the former middleweight title contender said Monday in a news conference. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> was convicted in the 1966 murder of three white men in a Paterson bar and served 19 years in prison before the indictment was finally dismissed last week. But <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, 50, dressed in a tan suede jacket, dark tie and navy blue pants, said during the 90-minute news conference that he harbors no bitterness over the system that jailed him. `` If I have learned anything in my life, it's that bitterness consumes the vessel that contains it,'' he said. The 1966 verdict against <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Artis </PERSON> was overturned, but the two black men were again convicted in 1976. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, who was serving a life term, was freed in 1985 by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, who found the conviction was tainted by racism and the witholding of information by prosecutors. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the judge's 1985 decision, and a <LOCATION> Passaic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> judge last Friday signed the papers dismissing the indictment, as requested by county prosecutors. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> had remained in seclusion, declining to discuss the case publicly. But on Monday he condemned over-zealous prosecutors, the horrors of the state prison system, the jailing of innocent people and racism. `` They sentenced me to a life of living death,'' he said. `` And there is no other way to describe the nature of a prison. Prison destroys everything valuable in the life of a human being.'' <PERSON> Artis </PERSON>, paroled in 1981, is serving a six-year prison term on an unrelated drug charge. His lawyer, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Steel </PERSON>, issued a plea for <PERSON> Artis </PERSON>' freedom, saying the judge who sentenced him in the drug case improperly took the voided murder convictions into account in the sentencing. The drug sentence is on appeal. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s cause was taken up in the 1970s by celebrities, who championed him as a symbol of racial injustice. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> wrote a ballad about the case, which played repeatedly in the background before the news conference. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> refused to blame the trial's prosecutors directly for his fate, but said `` racism is sleazy'' and referred to <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON>'s finding that the prosecution made `` an appeal to racism rather than reason. Since being freed, he said he has worked on his case nearly every day and his third book, `` No Holds Barred, No Bars To Hold,'' while living in southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said he had difficulty understanding how he came to serve nearly two decades in prison. `` One moment I'm a championship prize fighter, the next moment and 20 years after I'm reviled as a triple murderer,'' he said. `` The fact that the most productive years of my life, the ages of 29 and 50, have been stolen, the fact that I was deprived of seeing my children grow up, would n't you think I would have a right to be bitter?'' he said. But being bitter would give the state another victory, he said. `` That would make me an accomplice to their crime.
