<HEAD>Lawyer Says Husband To Blame For Children's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman charged with involuntary manslaughter says it was her husband who locked their two young children in a sun-baked car last summer, leading to the youngsters' deaths, her lawyer says <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Shields </PERSON>, 19, of White Township, relied on her husband, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Shields </PERSON>, 24, to take care of their children, <PERSON> Kristle </PERSON>, 3, and <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON>, 1, on Aug. 22, said lawyer <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> will `` testify his wife told him to watch the children while she went inside the house because she was ill,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said during opening remarks Monday in the first day of Mrs. Shield's trial Prosecutors called 11 witnesses Monday and were expected to call several more today before the defense began its case. The couple left a party early on Aug. 22 and drove to a relative's farmhouse, according to an affidavit by state police. Mrs. <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> slept in the car with the children from about 5 a.m. to 9 a.m., and <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> went into the house, police said. Then Mrs. <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> went into the house and asked her husband to take care of the children, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. Shields moved the car to a sunnier location and rolled up the windows, police said. When Mrs. <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> checked the children several hours later, she found <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> unconscious and <PERSON> Kristle </PERSON> gasping for breath, according to police. <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> was pronounced dead at the scene and his sister died the next day in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>'s Mercy Hospital. Autopsies showed both died of high temperatures. Mrs. <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> also is charged with endangering the welfare of children. Her husband faces identical charges and is scheduled to go on trial later this month in <LOCATION> Mifflin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Each defendant won a change of venue from <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> after defense attorneys argued pre-trial publicity made seating an impartial jury impossible there. They have been jailed since their arrests.
