<HEAD>Fifty-two Arrested in Illegal Animal Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifty-two people were arrested and at least $ 85,000 worth of exotic animals and organs were seized during an undercover investigation, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reported today that officers seized a variety of animal parts including genitalia from tigers and sea lions, rhinoceros horns and dried abalone. Several hundred male sex organs from other species were also seized, said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> and Game patrol chief at the department's <LOCATION> Yountville </LOCATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Napa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The operation began as an investigation into illegal trafficking in bear gall bladders, said <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>. Most of the charges involve poaching and commercialization of wildlife, both misdemeanor violations of the state Fish and Game Code, he said. <PERSON> Munroe </PERSON> said the animal parts were marketed mostly to the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> community as aphrodisiacs and general health foods. In some cases, he said, gall bladders from cows or pigs were sold as bear organs.
