<HEAD>Curfew Imposed In Sumgait, Site Of Rioting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet government spokesman said today a curfew was imposed in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, the city in <LOCATION> Azerbaidzhan </LOCATION> where rioting broke out two days ago. He said `` some mistakes'' had been made concerning a disputed territory that is home to tens of thousands of Armenians. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said the situation was calm but tense in <LOCATION> Azerbaidzhan </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, where ethnic hatred triggered demonstrations, violence and at least two deaths in recent days. He suggested the unrest resulted from a `` mistake'' made 65 years ago when a territory composed largely of ethnic Armenians was made part of neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaidzhan </LOCATION>. `` There were certain injuries'' in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, an industrial city where hooligans were blamed for touching off a riot Sunday, <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said. At his regular briefing today, the Soviet spokesman was peppered with questions about the unrest in the southern republics of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and Azerbaidzhan. However, he said he had few details. Foreign journalists have been barred from the region, and only sporadic reports from witnesses, activists and the official media have reached <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> was asked about reports that Soviet tanks are patrolling <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, that ethnic Azeris are attacking Armenians there and that there have been at least two deaths in the city. He responded that `` there is a curfew'' in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, but that he had not heard anything about tanks being sent into the city. `` The situation is calm there today, but it is tense,'' <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said. Asked if troops remained in the city today, he said, `` I do n't know, but I guess so Presumably.'' The violence in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, reported Monday by the official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, followed outbreaks 150 miles away in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, the contested region in <LOCATION> Azerbaidzhan </LOCATION>, and mass demonstrations in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. The demonstrators demanded that <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, which has been part of <LOCATION> Azerbaidzhan </LOCATION> since 1923, be made part of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Three-quarters of the area's 157,000 residents are Armenian. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said he did not have detailed reports from the entire region but that what information he had indicated `` everything is calm'' in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> and surrounding areas. `` The events that took place caused great concern to us,'' he said. `` We think it is not a proper way to settle the problems that have accumulated.'' <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> acknowledged, however, that the unrest apparently stemmed from `` some mistakes made in the national relations, and these mistakes should be rectified.'' Soviet authorities have pledged to reconsider the issue of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s parent republic, and <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON>'s statement seemed to indicate the region might be turned over to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. He did not, however, say when that might occur. Asked if he meant to say that <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> should be made part of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said: `` I meant there were some mistakes in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>.'' He described the region as `` a kind of enclave'' in <LOCATION> Azerbaidzhan </LOCATION> with 49 nationalities represented among the population that is nonetheless mostly Armenian. `` That is why we should be very tactful in handling this question in order not to cause differences between brothers and nationalities. The previous policy had some mistakes in this area,'' he said. On Friday, Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> appealed for `` civil maturity and restraint'' and promised the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> would review relations among the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s more than 100 nationalities Azerbaidzhan is the largest of three Soviet republics in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION>. It is bordered on the west by largely <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armenia </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and on the north by the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>.
