<HEAD>Dorm Takeover Ends at Hampshire College</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forty minority students at <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> have reached an agreement with the administration to end their week-long takeover of a dormitory, a college spokeswoman said today. The students had complained of racism at the private liberal arts school. `` By the end of the day we expect the agreement to be fully signed,'' said administration spokeswoman <PERSON> Melissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON>. Spokesmen for the protesters holding the <ORGANIZATION> Dakin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> office were out of the building and could not be reached for comment. College President <PERSON> Adele </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> met Monday with representatives of the blacks, Hispanics, Indians and other minorities who have held the small brick building since Feb. 23. Their 16 demands included the creation of the post of dean of multicultural affairs and for a full-time coordinator for the minority student group. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> last week offered the students $ 25,000 to spend as they please on their programs, but the negotiators rejected the offer. `` That's really an absurd amount for what is needed,'' protest spokeswoman <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Fearman </PERSON> said Monday. College spokeswoman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Wicks </PERSON> said the students evidently did not understand the college's budget. `` When you see our high tuition, you think there must be lots of extra money on campus,'' she said. `` We're ending this year on a deficit and they're asking us to come up with bucks in March. Yes, we want to be supportive, but in fact we do n't have the money.'' Tuition at the private liberal arts school was nearly $ 16,000 this year, she said. Minorities represent about 10 percent of the school's 1,100 students.
