<HEAD>`Glass Ceiling' Seen Blocking Women's Entry To Top Media Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FELIX GUTIERREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More women are working in entertainment and the news media, but they bump into a `` glass ceiling'' that prevents them from rising into top management jobs, experts told a conference on Women, Men and Media. `` While more women are hired, that does n't always translate up,'' said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> journalism professor <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, citing data gathered during a five-year study of women in media. `` I do see that glass ceiling,'' Ms. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> told the conference Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>. She described the `` glass ceiling'' as `` a transparent barrier'' that allows women to see top echelon jobs but blocks access to them. Women account for 66 percent of the nation's journalism graduates, but less than 2 percent of newspaper corporate management, 5 percent of publishers and general managers, and 13 percent of directing editors, she said. `` The employment of women in news media lags behind employment in the society overall,'' Ms. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. `` If current trends continue, women wo n't attain directing editorships on par with their level of the population until 2055.'' Despite gains in front of the television camera, Ms. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> reported similar patterns in broadcast management. She said no networks had a woman heading their news division, and only nine of 51 network news vice presidents are women. Local television stations also have few women in management, Ms. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. But she said radio stations employ women in proportion to the workforce. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON>, anchor on <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> television station <ORGANIZATION> KNBC </ORGANIZATION>, said some women in television are treated as `` shadow anchors'' to a male co-anchor, are assigned to `` soft stories'' and are not allowed to age. `` You do n't see very many female <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuralts </PERSON> on television, or women who look like <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON>, naming two veteran male newscasters. The three-day conference, which started Sunday, was organized by <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedan </PERSON>, author of the best-selling `` The Feminine Mystique'' and a visiting journalism professor at <ORGANIZATION> USC </ORGANIZATION>. An analysis of credits on 1986-87 network entertainment series found women employed more often as writers than as producers or directors, said <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Steenland </PERSON> of Wider Opportunities for Women. Seventeen of the top 20 shows had women writers. half had women producers and six had directors. <PERSON> Futurist </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Toffler </PERSON> said women have a chance to manage new media as communication becomes diversified by cable television and other outlets targeting `` micro markets'' within the mass audience. `` We're going to see two-tiered media,'' said <PERSON> Toffler </PERSON>. Mass media will cover major events, but customized media will provide information and entertainment to audiences defined by such characteristics as race, sex, interest or geographic area, he said. The conference was co-sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> USC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalism </ORGANIZATION>, the Institute for the Study of Women and Men, Women in Film, and the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZ