<TEXT>
 Republican <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, playing catch-up in the Southern presidential primaries, attacked <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in public and in new television commercials today as a vice president without record or accomplishment and a supporter of the arms-for-hostages deal with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s campaign began airing tough ads striking at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, as <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> escalated criticism of the vice president at appearances at <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` That's precisely what he did _ he supported the sale of arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said when asked about the new television attack. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> minority leader, accused <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of offering `` nine different answers'' on the Iran-Contra affair. `` But it's a fact he did support it,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` Now we're talking about credibility,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` When somebody gives you nine different answers on the same question, I think it's an issue.'' Trailing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the polls in most of the states voting next week, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> began a test-run of strong television ads in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and other selected <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> cities, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> campaign manager <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> said. The ads, which the <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> campaign produced but did not run during the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> campaign, depict <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as walking through snow but leaving no footprints, <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> said. He said the message was that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` ha