<HEAD>First Day of Expressway Reconstruction Not So Bad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first morning of reconstruction on the city's major highway link to the south passed without major traffic jams, police said today `` So far, so good,'' state police Sgt. <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Enright </PERSON> said of the traffic on the <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Expressway </PERSON>, one of the nation's busiest highways. Most commuters apparently heeded warnings about potential traffic problems and took other routes or public transportation. The project will widen the <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> from four lanes each way to five. During 6 -LCB- months of construction on southbound lanes this year, all traffic will share four lanes. The northbound lanes will be out of commission next year during the project's second phase. Some motorists had planned novel ways to cope with massive traffic jams they had expected. <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Coenen </PERSON> said bought tape-recorded `` talking books,'' such as <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Michener </PERSON>'s `` <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' to listen to while she sits in traffic. `` I think it's going to be like a huge, huge parking lot,'' says Ms. <PERSON> Coenen </PERSON>, who lives in northwest suburban <LOCATION> Elk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> and uses the <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Expressway </PERSON> to commute to her job as a health educator at <ORGANIZATION> Michael </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> on the city's <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>. `` I have visions of people taking folding chairs and tables and playing cards.'' `` I think it's going to be a real bad nightmare,'' says <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, 35, a hospital secretary who commutes from her home in south suburban <LOCATION> Evergreen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> to her job in south <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Expressway </PERSON>, an 11-mile stretch of concrete and asphalt, is the main link between <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and points south. Traffic from at least six other expressways feeds the <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> just south of downtown <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. State officials say the $ 210 million rebuilding job will be the largest highway project in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> history. `` The road is simply wearing out from old age and the pounding it has taken from traffic, particularly trucks,'' says <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Adorjan </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>. The state plans to close all four southbound lanes from March 13 to October 31, rerouting southbound traffic onto two of the four northbound lanes. The process will be reversed in the spring of 1989. The work began today with the closing of several lanes on each side of the freeway for a week to build traffic crossovers and patch the northbound side. As the project began, a psychiatrist recommended deep breaths, exercise or conversation as tension easers for stalled commuters. `` Drivers who are mentally prepared to face these difficulties can reduce the stress,'' says Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Glass </PERSON>, associate psychiatry professor and director of adult outpatient services at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. He said drivers could also use their stall time to learn a foreign language from taped lessons or dictate letters into a tape recorder.
