<HEAD>Court Makes It Easier to Deport Some Aliens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, making it easier to deport some aliens, today blocked further hearings for a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> man seeking to avoid return to his native <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>. The court ruled 8-0 that immigration officials, having decided an alien should be deported, generally are under no duty to reconsider the case when the alien says he has new evidence to support a bid for asylum. The decision is a defeat for Dr. <PERSON> Assibi </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON>, a native and citizen of <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> who graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> medical school and married a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen. Immigration officials moved to deport him in 1981 after he was convicted in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> of illegally attempting to obtain the narcotic drug demerol by fraud. He was given a one-year suspended prison sentence and was placed on probation for three years. The Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> found him deportable and the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld that decision. <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON> sought to reopen his case in 1985 and seek asylum in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from the military dictatorship of Flight Lieutenant <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rawlings </PERSON>, who regained power in <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> in a Dec. 31, 1981, military coup. <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON> said he had new evidence that his life might be in danger if he was forced to return to <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> based on a 1984 visit to him by <PERSON> Abukari </PERSON> <PERSON> Alhassan </PERSON>, secretary of housing and construction in the <PERSON> Rawlings </PERSON> regime. <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON> said he believed <PERSON> Alhassan </PERSON> was trying to lure him back to <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> so officials there could torture him to extract information about opponents of the <PERSON> Rawlings </PERSON> regime. <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON> said his brother escaped capture by the regime and fled into hiding and also said his lifelong friend, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamidu </PERSON>, is regarded as the number one enemy of the <PERSON> Rawlings </PERSON> government. The <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> refused to reopen <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON>'s case, noting that <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON> did not initially seek asylum when he contested his deportation. But the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 ordered the board to reconsider granting <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON> asylum. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration that the appeals court should have deferred to the decision of the immigration board. Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, writing for the court, said aliens seeking to reopen their deportation cases have the difficult task of proving that immigration officials abused their discretion in refusing to do so. `` There is a strong public interest in bringing litigation to a close as promptly as is consistent with the interest in giving the adversaries a fair opportunity to develop and present their respective cases,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said. `` We have no hesitation in concluding that the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> did not abuse its discretion when it held that <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON> had not reasonably explained his failure to apply for asylum prior to the completion of the initial deportation proceeding,'' he said. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who only recently joined the court, did not take part in the decision. The case is <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Abudu </PERSON>, 86-1128.
