<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A survey released today says that the threat of malpractice suits caused 12 percent of obstetricians to close their practices last year and that two-thirds leave the field before age 55. The survey, conducted in October and November for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Obstetricians </ORGANIZATION> and Gynecologists, showed that the national rate for physicians dropping obstetrics has remained at 12 percent for the last two years, but that the age of those quitting is getting younger. `` If this trend continues, we are going to see more and more physicians leaving obstetrics at the height of their professional ability,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Jimmie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gleason </PERSON>, chairman of the doctors' committee on professional liability `` We are looking at a situation where obstetrics is being concentrated more and more in large urban and suburban areas.'' In <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the number of doctors no longer delivering babies has reached 25 percent, about twice the national average, and 75 percent of those quitting in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> are doing so before the age 55, also far above the national average. Malpractice insurance premiums for obstetricians in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> now average about $ 52,000 a year, the survey shows. The national average has risen from $ 10,946 in 1982 to $ 37,015 in 1987, according to the report. <PERSON> Gleason </PERSON> said the survey revealed `` several disturbing trends'' in the care of high-risk pregnancies. Twenty-seven of the surveyed doctors said they were limiting the number of high-risk cases they will take, compared to 23 percent in 1985, and 18 percent in 1982. The survey showed that seven out of 10 obstetrician-gynecologists nationally have been sued at some point in their career. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, 55 percent of the practicioners have been sued two or more times. Fifty-two percent of the suits involved obstetric cases, with 31 percent of these cases for claims of neurologically-impaired infants, and 15 percent for claims of stillbirths or infant deaths, the survey showed. Of the claims resolved, 36 percent were dropped without payment. Of those not dropped, 79 percent were settled with payment. The survey showed that obstetrician-gynecologists had a mean gross income in 1986 of $ 296,133, with the highest gross in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, with $ 387,022, and in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, with $ 323,252. The mean gross income increased by $ 81,122 from 1984 to 1986, the survey showed. The average medical practice overhead reported was $ 147,029, with the average for <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> at $ 190,882. <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> conducted the survey for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Obstetricians </ORGANIZATION> and Gynecologists.
