<HEAD>Court Declines to Decide if Mississippi or Federal Government
Controls Gulf Area</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts penultimate graf, Justices Thurgood, to say who did
not participate.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today declined to decide yet whether the state or the federal government should control a Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> area off <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s southwestern coastline. Rejecting arguments by the state's lawyers, the court ruled 7-0 that more information is needed before such a determination is made. <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> had sought a ruling that its southwestern coastline extends beyond several barrier islands and into <LOCATION> Chandeleur </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION>, south of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Sound. Control of an area of about 150 square miles of the gulf, along with control of the natural resources there, remains in dispute. The case acted on today has, in varying forms, been before the high court since 1956, when the justices first invoked their `` original jurisdiction'' to hear the controversy before it had been aired in any lower court. In such cases, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> functions as a trial court and acts on the recommendations of a court-appointed `` special master.'' In this case, retired Judge <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> is serving as the special master. He recommended that <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s pressing for a ruling that gives it control of the disputed gulf area should be ruled premature. Writing for the court today, Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> agreed. He said <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s arguments `` are overruled but without prejudice to the advancement of such claims as any party might have with respect to the area south of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> in the vicinity of <LOCATION> Chandeleur </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> in an appropriate separate chapter of these proceedings.'' The <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Sound is a body of water between the state's mainland and a line of barrier islands several miles offshore In 1985, the justices ruled that <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> _ and not the federal government _ own their respective portions of the sound's bed and therefore control the natural resources there. <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said the high court would retain jurisdiction in the case, raising the likelihood that still another ruling on the issue is in the court's future. Justices <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> did not participate in the decision. The case is <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Boundardy Case, 9 Original.
