<HEAD>Tritium Escape Reported At SRP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A `` puff'' of tritium escaped from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> Plant today, but posed no hazard to the public, officials said. Spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Felder </PERSON> said about 20,000 curies of tritium, a radioactive isotope of hydrogen, were released at 6:18 a.m. this morning during routine operations. <PERSON> Felder </PERSON> characterized the release as `` a puff'' and said it lasted less than a minute. The weapons production facility at the plant makes material used in the production of nuclear weapons, and <PERSON> Felder </PERSON> said details on the process under way when the release occurred are classified. The exposure at the plant boundary, about six miles from the H Chemical Separations Area where the release occurred, was about 0.04 millirems, <PERSON> Felder </PERSON> said. By comparison, he said a normal chest X-ray is 20 millirems. Two employees in the work area at the time of the release were undergoing tests to see if they suffered any ill effects. They were wearing full protective gear at the time, he said. All plant operations have returned to normal, he said. <PERSON> Felder </PERSON> said an initial assessment of the cause of the release indicates equipmment malfunction. However, an investigation will be conducted. The last such release at the plant occurred July 31, 1987, when a dosage of .2 millirems was measured at the plant's boundary. The plant's reactors were reduced to half power last year amid concerns over the cooling system, and <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> officials told a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Monday that the reactors could be running at full capacity by 1990. <PERSON> Felder </PERSON> said this morning the process in which the tritium was released is separate from that involving the reactors and would not affect the reactor plans.
