<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 How does a presidential candidate campaign for 20 far-flung contests held on the same day? The answer is television. The primaries and caucuses of March 8, Super Tuesday, are being held in states and territories from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, an unprecedented sweep across more than 150 media markets with more than 500 television stations. Television is as critical on the vast Super Tuesday battleground as grass-roots organizing was in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> fired an opening salvo, starting a test-run of tough television ads in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> ad, which the <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> campaign produced but did not run during the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> campaign, depicts Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> walking through snow but leaving no footprints. The message, said <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> campaign manager <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>, was that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` has held all these big jobs'' yet left no mark. The other <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> ad, running in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, injects the Iran-Contra affair into the campaign. It says <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` supported arms for hostages,'' `` waffles on taxes'' and opposes legislation limiting textile imports, a bill <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> supports and that is popular in the textile-producing <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> last week that he opposes the textile bill as protectionist. Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> also was taking the offensive with two critical ads. One featured Rep. <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Leath </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> criticizing <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> rivals <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> Jr. The other was a retooled version of an ad that was considered a key factor in <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s victory over <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> last week in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. At the outset of his campaign, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> mentioned Belgian endive, a kind of yuppie lettuce, as an example of how <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> farmers could diversify their crops. The <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> ad criticizes the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor's positions on trade and farm issues, and ends with a voice saying sarcastically: `` Belgian endive?'' Many observers said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> made a major error in not responding with an ad of his own _ a situation that wo n't be repeated. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dach </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign had prepared a negative ad about <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> and would use it soon, possibly starting today, in Super Tuesday states. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> has also revived an ad that was seen as having a big impact in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> _ in which he criticizes <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> for stifling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto sales in that nation with stiff tariffs, and threatens to respond in kind. See how many Hyundais the Koreans can sell here at $ 48,000 apiece, he tells viewers. And <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> has a commercial featuring the popular Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, a Democrat who has ample clout with senior citizens. Pepper is from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the second-biggest Super Tuesday state. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has ads featuring fellow <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> politician <PERSON> Tip </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker, and has been running a biographical spot in which he stresses his economic accomplishments as governor. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has mounted particularly strong efforts in four states with pockets of ethnic or liberal voters: <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> have focused on the border states that lie near their respective homes of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who bypassed early contests to stress the Super Tuesday states, took out a loan Monday to pay for a media blitz, a campaign spokesman said. `` We're going to saturate Super Tuesday. ... We want to pour it on,'' said press spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Kopp </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s state campaign treasurer in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> had taken a $ 1 million line of credit against which money would be borrowed for a 20-state advertising campaign. <PERSON> Kopp </PERSON> said new <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> commercials would go on the air today. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> has already made national cable television buys and purchases of time on individual stations in most of the Super Tuesday states. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was first on the air in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, where he once lived. He has been running a biographical ad. Republican rival Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> has concentrated his advertising money in seven Super Tuesday states, said his political director, <P