<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge today cleared the way for enforcement of a federal regulation intended to save endangered sea turtles by throwing out a suit filed by shrimpers who say the rule will ruin their business. Shrimpers said they would defy the regulation, which goes into effect today. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> brushed aside vehement arguments from shrimpers battling the requirement that they use bulky traps called turtle excluder devices, commonly called TEDs, which are intended to eject trapped turtles from nets. `` I do n't care if he upheld it. It's a bad law, and the shrimpers ai n't going to live by it,'' said Tee <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mialjevich </PERSON> of Concerned Shrimpers of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, which filed suit against the law. Critics say the devices do n't always work and that they allow shrimp to escape. <PERSON> Mialjevich </PERSON> said shrimpers in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, where the law has been in effect since Jan. 1, experienced reductions of 35 percent to 50 percent of their catches. The law was also scheduled to go into effect off the coast of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> today. Shrimpers had argued that there was not enough evidence to show that the TEDs would be effective in protecting the endangered turtles. `` A review of the administrative record demonstrates that -LRB- shrimpers' -RRB- arguments are unfounded in most aspects,'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> wrote. `` From the outset, the Secretary -LRB- of <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- through the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> collected scientific information from sea turtle experts from states, universities and the private sector.'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> had said in advance that his ruling would not determine the usefulness or effectiveness of the controversial devices, but would address only whether the government had followed proper procedures when it imposed the legislation. The outcry against the TEDs spread even to the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, where a law was passed forbidding state officials from enforcing the new regulations. The state attorney general's office had joined the shrimpers' suit, but <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> dismissed the state from the case, saying the shrimpers were capable of speaking for themselves State officials were not sure how they would act. <PERSON> Corky </PERSON> <PERSON> Perret </PERSON>, assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION>, said his department is caught in a `` Catch-22'' situation between state and federal law. `` Until I get some legal, firm position to sit on, I guess I'm up in the air,'' <PERSON> Perret </PERSON> said
