<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senators <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif., called on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> today to strictly penalize <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries that fail to cooperate with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in its effort to combat drug <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> for a Drug Free America the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration must decide the national security interest of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> before being concerned about <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, particularly <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was to officially announce that <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has failed to cooperate with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but will not impose forceful sanctions in an effort to force the ouster of Central American country's military strongman, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. The president also was to reject calls to decertify <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, which have been criticized heavily for failing to cut the flow of drugs to this country. <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> said many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> believe the certification process has not been used properly by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. Under the 1986 law, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> is to decertify and cut off aid to countries `` not fully cooperating'' with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to combat drug traffic.. `` This year, the good news is that <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is on the list,'' said <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> `` On the other hand, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> are n't. We'll have to examine why <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is certified. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> is a country under siege and we will have to examine that. We have to ask ourselves what is the national interest. I think we have to continue to apply pressure against these countries.'' He said the law will be changed next year to require a bilateral agreement between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nations `` so that there will be a country-by-country certification, rather than one list including all of them. We will tell them in advance what we expect of them and we will be able to grade them on how they do. That will be more helpful to this country.'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> was particularly upset that the administration did not decertify <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, a country that borders on his state of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` How can we delude ourselves into thinking that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> should be certified,'' he said. `` They should not. They have not cooperated fully with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. If we are going to send young drug agents into <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, we should demand full cooperation and not wink at it. The 1986 act spelled out what is to be expected, and it has not been done.'' <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> both said the president relies too heavily on the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for the basis of his certification of a country. `` State is willing to be too tolerant in this area,'' said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Narcotics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> felt for years that <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> was the primary cause of concern for the nation's drug problem but now `` it seems that we have an entire hemisphere to worry about. The so-called spread of Communist influence is the least of our worries in this region at this point in time.''
