<HEAD>Vermont Primary Overshadowed By Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with turnout, inserting new 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MEG DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>'s `` beauty contest'' primary today has been largely overshadowed by preparations for next week's delegate-heavy Super Tuesday primaries, political observers say Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> _ who won the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> caucuses over the weekend _ were considered the front-runners here, continuing to play on their ties to the region. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> native, has a summer home in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is the governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Vermont Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> predicted a record turnout of 125,000 voters. Several communities reported strong voting today under sunny skies, but turnout in the state's largest city, <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, was running behind four years ago. Some had predicted that the <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> primary _ falling between the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> primary and Super Tuesday, March 8 _ would take on more importance this year. But the primary has attracted little attention. `` I think what we're seeing is we're getting jumped by Super Tuesday,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> just got lost in the shuffle,'' said <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a political science professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION>. `` Those timing factors when combined with the fact the <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> primary is a beauty contest ... led to an incredible loss of interest.'' Tuesday's voting does not choose delegates; Vermonters merely state their preferences in the non-binding primary. Delegates to the national conventions will be elected at state conventions, a process that begins in April with local caucuses to elect delegates to the state convention. The candidates sent a lot of surrogates to stump for them, but made few personal appearances. `` We got to see very little of the candidates. We saw their mothers, their wives, their children, but we did n't see much of them,'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. Spokesmen for the candidates say attention now is on winning delegates in local caucuses. `` That's our focus, that's where our energy is going even now,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, a campaign coordinator for <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who scored a surprisingly strong second in the weekend <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Democratic caucuses. `` I think there's a recognition that the -LRB- <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> -RRB- primary is the beginning of building for the caucus,'' said <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Yager </PERSON> of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign. But <PERSON> Yager </PERSON> maintains <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> probably gets more attention from candidates than some of the 20 individual Super Tuesday states. `` No single state gets a lot of one-on-one attention,'' she said. Although non-binding, the <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> primary has served an important purpose in past years. In 1980, former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> used a win in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> to embarrass Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., in his own back yard The same year, a strong second-place finish in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> gave Republican <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>'s campaign a major boost. In 1984, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>'s overwhelming defeat of <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> helped him shed his image as a dark horse.
