<FIRST>r a AM-RuralPoor Bjt-1stAdd   03-01 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rural Poor, Bjt - 1st Add,0875</SECOND>
<HEAD>TCHULA, Miss.: long-term decline.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Apparel manufacturing is <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s leader in employment. Besides that, furniture building is centered in the <LOCATION> Tupelo </LOCATION> area, and catfish processing employs people in the Delta. Since the 1960s, manufacturing has employed more people than farming in this state where 70 percent of the people live outside urban areas _ and yet in some recent years the leading source of income in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> was neither. It was government `` transfer payments'' _ Aid to Families with Dependent Children, Social Security, food stamps. `` As the economy becomes more automated, more geared toward people with skills,'' <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> said, `` you're going to see more people left out.'' Asked the solution, he quoted <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s new governor, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON>: `` Education, education, education.'' Without that, high-technology companies will continue to stay away, agreed <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, a lawyer working for the <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>. `` You've got to get them -LRB- students -RRB- enough math and English so that the Vo-Tech can teach them to work for a <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION>.'' In rural areas nationally, 18 percent of people fall below the poverty level, about $ 11,200 for a family of four, according to 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> figures. That's the same rate as in inner-cities. `` I do n't think the people who are masterminding this economy are paying attention to this,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Zippert </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperatives </ORGANIZATION>, a group based in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> that helps family farmers hold onto their land. `` It's a little like the underclass question of the urban ghetto _ that there's going to be a permanent class that's going to be left behind.'' Left behind is a fitting description. `` In one year, rural areas across the country lost 632,000 people to metro areas due to migration,'' <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., has said `` That's like saying that all of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> migrated in one year.'' Those who leave tend to be the best educated, say officials, lamenting the rural `` brain drain.'' It's not that nothing is being done to address the rural-urban economic restructuring that <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has termed `` just as profound as what was happening in the <LOCATION> Rustbelt </LOCATION>.'' But many observers of the rural poor say the efforts of government are piecemeal and inadequate. Federal funding for a variety of rural development programs added up to about $ 1.6 billion last year, according to a study just completed by the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Change </ORGANIZATION>, a research and advocacy group in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> Those programs included grant and loan programs of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> _ from which <LOCATION> Tchula </LOCATION> received its grant _ and the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> and other departments. `` The funding levels have shrunk radically from what they were at the end of the Carter administration,'' said <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> DeWeaver </PERSON>, who led the study. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's policy has been to decentralize efforts to aid rural development, noted the economic research organization <ORGANIZATION> MDC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, in a report last month. `` The federal government now dictates fewer rules and provides fewer dollars. As a result,'' said <ORGANIZATION> MDC </ORGANIZATION>, `` ... there is a surge of economic and social initiatives in state governments throughout the country.'' Besides a new emphasis on improving education in virtually all Southern states, initiatives cited by <ORGANIZATION> MDC </ORGANIZATION> included: a bank in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> that focuses mainly on rural economic development; innovative literacy projects in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>; and a biracial group in struggling <LOCATION> Noxubee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, that promotes home-grown businesses. Nonetheless, the study cited `` many more dark rural places still lacking the resources, the information, and the encouragement'' to make significant economic progress, and it called for more carefully targeted federal and private-sector help in giving isolated places access to capital and management assistance, education and training. Just outside of <LOCATION> Tchula </LOCATION>, the members of the <LOCATION> Mileston </LOCATION> Co-op know what a little outside help can mean. Sitting in the spare country store that the co-op of black farmers has owned for 40 years, <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON>, the acting president, talked about the donation they received from FarmAid, the charity fund created by country musicians. Some of the members, whose cotton farms average about 50 acres, used the money to pay delinquent taxes or overdue rent on land or old fertilizer bills. `` I can remember one fella,'' <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said, `` he had everything, but he could n't get diesel _ so that helped him.'' In the store, the afternoon gathering place now a month before planting time, the co-op members say they could use a different kind of outside help. They'd like to restart their cotton gin, which closed a few years ago because of drought-stricken crops and lack of money _ and they'd like to diversify, maybe open a plant that would process, package and freeze vegetables grown in their fields. A plant like that would employ some of the workers displaced by planting and picking machines. First, though, they'd need the expertise to help ensure profitability, and second, the start-up investment. The idea is not to get rich, the men said, but to employ people and give the next generation a chance to stay here. `` I realize it would n't cure the problem,'' <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said, `` but that would help some.''
