 The Foreign Ministry has lodged a protest with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy over the `` subversive thrust'' of <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> broadcasts on nationalist unrest in the Baltic republics, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. The official news agency charged Monday that <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> reports beamed into the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` have been crudely distorting historical facts, making provocative insinuations about the growth of nationalist sentiment in the Baltic republics of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and expressing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for forces that do not accept the social system in this country.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said today: `` The Soviet charges are false. We are covering stories about nationality problems in the <ORGANIZATION> Baltics </ORGANIZATION> and elsewhere in the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> fairly and honestly. We have tens of millions of listeners in the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> and the Soviet authorities do n't want them to hear the message so they attack the messenger. The complaints are unfounded and we'll just keep doing our job.'' There have been a number of nationalist demonstrations in recent months in the once-independent republics of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government-operated radio has taken a `` dramatically increased subversive thrust'' in reporting on the situation in the Baltic region. The news agency said the protest was made to the <LOCATION> U.S. </