<HEAD>Hobbs Says Goodbye to John Roger The Alligator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOBBS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Roger </PERSON>, the alligator who was flushed into the <PERSON> Hobbs </PERSON> sewer system as a baby and lived a pampered life in his own solar home at the city water treatment plant, was buried Tuesday. The alligator was buried 16 years after sewer workers named <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> found the 24-inch reptile swimming in an effluent pond. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> was 7 feet, 9 inches long at the time of his death Monday. He lived in a fenced compound that included a solar-heated home, diving pond and grass knoll for sunbathing. The alligator's body was found at the compound at the bottom of his pool. He apparently had gone for a post-hibernation swim. No necropsy was scheduled but officials suspected the alligator died of pneumonia. State Sen. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, who was city manager at the time <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> was adopted, recalled the alligator was fond of frogs. `` There were months where there was n't a live frog in this town,'' <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> said. `` Kids found out that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> liked frogs _ live frogs _ and they'd go out and find them, then throw them over the fence of his compound.''
