<HEAD>Plane Crash Kills 17 In South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A small passenger plane exploded in flight Tuesday and crashed in an industrial area east of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, killing all 17 people on board, the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported. The radio said the plane was operated by <ORGANIZATION> Comair </ORGANIZATION>, a private commercial airline that flies between <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and towns in north and central <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The twin-engine plane, a Brazilian-made Bandeirante turboprop, was en route to <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> from the northern border town of <LOCATION> Phalaborwa </LOCATION> when it crashed, state-run South African Broadcasting reported. It said all 15 passengers and two crew members aboard were killed. There was no immediate indication what caused the crash. Witnesses told reporters they heard an explosion and saw what appeared to be two pieces of the plane plunge to the ground. The plane went down in an area called <LOCATION> Wadeville </LOCATION>, about six miles east of downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. The identities of the victims were not immediately known. The Bandeirante can accommodate up to 18 passengers.
