<HEAD>Subway Ridership Up for 3rd Straight Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ridership on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> subways increased for the third straight year in 1987 to its highest level in 13 years, the <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday. TA President <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunn </PERSON> attributed much of the increase to new and overhauled cars on some lines and a boost in the number of clean cars. Officials also said subway crime was down 8.1 percent for serious felonies from 1986. TA spokesman <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Leary </PERSON> said there were 12,888 felonies on the subways last year compared with 14,030 in the previous 12 months. <PERSON> Gunn </PERSON> said 3,626,000 people rode the subways on an average weekday last year, up by 216,000 from 1984 and 103,000 from 1986. In all, 1.059 billion passengers rode the subways last year, up 29 million from 1986 and 62 million from 1984. <PERSON> Gunn </PERSON> said that 94 percent of the subway fleet should be graffiti-free by the end of this year.
