<HEAD>Bosch Release Order Stayed Pending Government Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge ordered the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday to free an anti-Castro activist who has been in a Venezuelan prison for 11 years on bond, but he stayed his order to allow the agency to appeal. Even if <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> won his freedom, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials were waiting in the wings to take custody of him, they said Tuesday. <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON>, a hero in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> community, has been in jail since he arrived last month from <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, where he spent 11 years in prison despite being acquitted three times of bombing a Cuban airliner. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities said <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> had violated parole by fleeing this country in 1974 while on probation for planning a bazooka attack on a Polish ship in the port of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> in 1968, and conspiring to plant bombs on other ships. <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Lourdes </PERSON>, said outside court that she was pleased with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryskamp </PERSON>'s order. But, she added, `` I am just confused and upset that now this is going to be appealed and they can stall another week or more. To me, it's just a farce, a political farce. <PERSON> Ryskamp </PERSON> called <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON>'s imprisonment until a scheduled March 21 parole hearing `` totally arbitrary and capricious.'' <PERSON> Ryskamp </PERSON> said Parole Commissioner <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackenzie </PERSON> <PERSON> Rast </PERSON> used `` tunnel vision in picking out those facts he wants to rely upon'' when he ordered <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> to remain jailed. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Senatore </PERSON> said he would appeal <PERSON> Ryskamp </PERSON>'s decision to the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, and the judge granted a temporary stay of his release order. Even if the appeals court upholds <PERSON> Ryskamp </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> also can not be released until his lawyers convince the INS. `` We of course have a detainer on him and would be holding him on an immigration violation,'' said <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> district director <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> has targeted <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> for exclusion hearings and possible deportation because he entered the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> without legal immigration documents last month after his release from a Venezuelan prison. <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> officials have said they will not permit <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON>'s release and have labeled him a terrorist because of his conviction for conspiring to bomb the Polish ship. Parole officials also accused him of consorting with known criminals. On the probation commission order, <PERSON> Ryskamp </PERSON> said <PERSON> Rast </PERSON> went beyond the facts on record to conclude that <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> should be held. The judge said <PERSON> Rast </PERSON> apparently considered <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON>'s acquittals in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> as a strike against him and wrongly considered `` reported'' past associations of <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> with known criminals. `` If that's going to be the basis of denying somebody their liberty rights, then it's a sad day for the Constitution,'' said <PERSON> Ryskamp </PERSON>. The judge also noted that <PERSON> Rast </PERSON> evidently reviewed information in <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON>'s parole file which was never disclosed to <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON>. The judge also noted that <PERSON> Rast </PERSON> ignored the recommendation of a probation officer who interviewed <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> and concluded there was no risk that he would flee. <PERSON> Ryskamp </PERSON> set bond at $ 250,000 and said that if <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> is freed he can not make public appearances or statements or identify himself with any militant groups opposing the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> government of <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>. He also could not receive more than five visitors in his home at any one time and would be required to report in three times a day by telephone.
