<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pro-choice groups filed 229,128 signatures Tuesday in support of a statewide vote on whether <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> should continue to pay for poor women's abortions. That gave the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Choice </ORGANIZATION> coalition more than 100,000 names above the minimum needed to put the issue on the Nov. 8 ballot and suspend a new law that will halt welfare abortion funding beginning March 29. However, the petitions may have been filed too late to avoid a temporary funding cutoff. `` We have every reason to believe that 29 days is enough time'' to confirm the required 119,829 valid signatures and put the law on hold, said <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Frey </PERSON>, speaking for the coalition. `` I would find that very unlikely,'' responded Elections Director <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. He said election-year petition certification normally takes 45 days to 60 days. Both <PERSON> Frey </PERSON> and Right to Life of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Listing </PERSON> said they were confident the signatures will be certified. `` It's a large pad. It's certainly enough to, I think, place it on the ballot,'' Listing said. Both sides have estimated the statewide campaign to sway referendum votes will cost $ 2 million to $ 3 million. The petition drive that ended Tuesday was the second in as many years dealing with welfare abortion funding. Since 1978, Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>, a Democrat, and his Republican predecessor, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON>, have used their veto power 17 times to preserve state-paid abortions for the poor. Right to Life initiated the no-funding law last year with a petition drive intended to avoid the veto. In <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, anyone who can gather 191,726 valid signatures can place before the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> a measure that, if approved by both houses, becomes law without the governor's signature. After gathering about 400,000 signatures, the Right to Life-written proposal breezed through the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> and became law. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> is one of 14 states that uses taxpayer money to finance abortions for the poor. In 1986, the most recent year for which a final tally is available, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> paid about $ 5.8 million for 18,600 abortions.
