<HEAD>Peace Talks Poised For Crucial Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Peace talks on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> open their most crucial and fragile phase on Wednesday, one that is widely hoped to produce a settlement to end a conflict that has claimed more than a million lives. But complex and potentially disruptive issues remain to be resolved during the United Nations-sponsored talks before a package of agreements, drawn up during almost six years of bargaining, finally can be completed. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> has said the new round of talks will focus on closing the gap between the varying timetables for withdrawing an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops. But likely to dominate the talks is a question that is formally outside their scope: Who will be in charge in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> until all Soviet troops have moved out? Delegates from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> both said Tuesday that they have come to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to finalize a settlement to end the 9-year-old conflict. But <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Zain </PERSON> <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> said his country would decide next week whether it was prepared to sign the peace package with the present Marxist government of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, which it does not recognize. <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is continuing to press for the formation of a transitional government to coincide with the withdrawal of Soviet troops. Without it, he said, there can be no peace. But he said `` we have come to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> with a constructive attitude to finalize the text'' of the four-agreement package. Meanwhile, the head of the Afghan delegation, foreign minister <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON>, told a news conference that he was looking forward to the new round with a `` sense of full optimism.'' The present leadership, he said, were `` not ambitious'' about retaining power. He said the timetable for the withdrawal was `` within negotiable range.'' The negotiations have come under mounting pressure since Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> announced Feb. 8 that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will withdraw its troops beginning on May 15 if a final deal is sealed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> by March 15. He said the withdrawal could be completed in 10 months. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> originally demanded that the troops quit in three months but has gradually widened that span to eight months. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> wants the settlement to include the transitional government because it could oversee the safe return of more than 5 million anti-Soviet Afghan refugees, one-third of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s pre-war population <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of creating last-minute obstacles to an accord and said the makeup of the government should be left to the Afghans. The alliance of Pakistan-based Afghan resistance groups, claiming to represent 200,000 Moslem guerrillas, responded last week by revealing its own plan for a government. It has ruled out any power-sharing with <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> but offered a minor role to `` Moslems presently living in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>,'' a formula that could refer to moderates in the present government. <PERSON> Yunis </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalis </PERSON>, chairman of the seven-group alliance, vowed the guerrillas wo n't lay down their arms until the `` Islamic government'' is set up. Predictably, that concept has been rejected by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON>, who heads the Afghan delegation in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> says he represents the `` only legal government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> which has been recognized by 80 countries.'' <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> so far has not given its formal support to the guerrilla proposal and has hinted it prefers a more broad-based approach. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which along with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is to guarantee implementation of the peace package, has been ambivalent in its reaction to the calls for an interim government. But the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, in a non-binding resolution Monday, urged formation of an interim government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> that is acceptable to the Afghan resistance. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Undersecretary of State <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON>, visiting <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> last week, said the guerrilla plan was a `` very welcome step towards the resolution of the Afghan problem.'' There has also been a lack of clear signals on when <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> would be prepared to cut off its aid to the guerrillas, reported to have been about $ 700 million last year. The Afghan monarchy was overthrown in 1978 and a communist government was installed. The Soviets intervened at the request of the embattled new Marxist government.
