<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has failed to stop the heavy influx of illicit drugs into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a group of congressmen told a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> conference on drugs Tuesday. Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., said the administration has earned nothing more than a `` C'' grade for its efforts in the so-called war on drugs Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, chided administration officials, including President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, for claiming the battle against drugs was being won. `` If we are winning the war on drugs, I wish the commanders would go out and tell it to the troops in the field,'' <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> said, drawing a standing ovation from a cheering crowd of about 2,000 at the White House Conference on a <LOCATION> Drug-Free </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` It's tragic to believe we are winning this battle against drugs when we have n't even fired the first shot,'' said <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON>, who is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Narcotics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He and six other members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> criticized the administration, as well as their own colleagues, for not taking such actions as sanctions toward <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> countries who do not cooperate with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> in trying to combat drug trafficking. They urged the creation of a drug czar to oversee the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> anti-drug efforts, the use of military forces for the interdiction of drugs from <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> countries and the mandatory, random testing of railroad employees. <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> were joined at the Congressional Forum of the five-day White House drug conference by Sens. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif., and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., and Reps. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> English, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clay </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> The conference, which was required by a 1986 anti-drug law, is bringing together drug abuse experts who will submit a final report and recommend solutions to the president and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this summer. <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> told the enthusiastic crowd: `` We need to get away from a policy of containment. We want you to come up with a plan for victory. Let's fight it like we fought World War II, not like <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. Let's fight to win.'' <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> and several others praised the role first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has played during the past seven years in her anti-drug campaign, `` Say No to Drugs.'' `` Thank God, we have <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> said. `` She is the only voice we have in this administration. We have no domestic or foreign policy on drugs. If you want to fight this war, you have to put up the resources for the boys in the front lines.'' <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> also said there has been a lack of resources assigned to the the battle against drugs. `` Nothing is a bigger threat internally or externally than the use of drugs,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. `` We have to focus on the problem and set priorities before it engulfs us completely.'' <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> also urged <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to impose severe sanctions against Latin American countries, particularly <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, if they refuse to cooperate with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in combatting drug trafficking. Under the 1986 law, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is to decertify and cut off aid to countries `` not fully cooperating'' with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to combat drug traffic. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> decided Tuesday that <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> have not cooperated with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to stop the drug smuggling to American markets. But <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Wrobleski </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official responsible for narcotics matters, said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> planned no steps to penalize <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> economically beyond measures already taken. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> certified that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> are cooperating with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug enforcement efforts, but Ms. <PERSON> Wrobleski </PERSON> said the president indicated that `` these countries should do more.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will `` wait and see'' if <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s military-dominated government improves its cooperation before deciding on additional sanctions, she said. The decisions concerning <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> will have no economic impact on them, partly because none is a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid recipient. <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> said many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> believe the administration has not used the certification process properly. `` This year, the good news is that <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is on the list,'' <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> said. `` On the other hand, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> are n't. ... I think we have to continue to apply pressure against these countries.''
