<HEAD>Construction Spending Down 2.9 Percent in January</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Construction spending fell 2.9 percent in January, the biggest decline in 10 months, reflecting widespread weakness in all sectors of the building industry, the government reported Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said construction spending fell to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 395.2 billion in January following a revised 0.4 percent advance in December. Economists said the decline was bigger than expected and will likely mean that construction will be a drag on overall economic growth in the first quarter of 1988. `` What was surprising about the figures was how widespread and pervasive the weakness was. Virtually every category from housing to industrial to hotels and motels did poorly in January,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumichrast </PERSON>, an economist and publisher of a construction industry newsletter, said he expects housing starts to fall by about 15 percent this year and non-residential construction to drop by 10 percent `` I have n't found any area in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with strong housing activity. The only strong area is public construction, which I think will rise by about 4 percent,'' <PERSON> Sumichrast </PERSON> said. The January decline was the largest since a 3.3 percent drop in March 1987, but some analysts said unusually severe weather in January may have contributed to the decline. Residential contruction fell 2.6 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 191.3 billion as construction of single-family homes fell 2.2 percent and multi-family construction dropped 6.4 percent. Analysts said single-family construction will strengthen in coming months because of recent mortgage-rate declines, but they forecast further declines in apartment building because of continued high vacancy rates. Non-residential construction fell 2.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 90.9 billion, reflecting declines in office construction, hotels, factories and shopping centers. Government construction spending was off 4.9 percent in January to a rate of $ 74.3 billion. The weakness in the public sector was led by a 3.9 percent fall in the largest government construction area, highway building, which declined to $ 24.8 billion.
