<FIRST>r w AM-DigitalAudio     03-01 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Digital Audio,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Study Says DAT Anti-Copying System Is Flawed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposed electronic encoding system designed to prevent music from being copied by new digital audio tape recorders is flawed, the government said Tuesday in a report that boosted efforts to introduce the new machines in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` There is no reason at this point why manufacturers should not be selling'' digital recorders in this country, said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> of the Home Recording Rights Coalition. But recording industry officials promised to sue any manufacturer that tries to sell the machines in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> before the copying issue is resolved, either legislatively or through industry negotiations. Digital audio tape, or DAT, recorders can make copies of compact disc recordings without discernible loss of quality. The recording industry fears that such high-quality copying would cut into their compact disc profits. DAT recorders costing about $ 2,000 were introduced last year in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. But manufacturers have held off bringing them to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where pending legislation in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would require DAT recorders to contain an anti-taping chip that would prevent home recordings. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, a DAT manufacturer, said the study's results would not effect the company's decisions on when to introduce the recorders in <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We're not rushing to market,'' <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. He said <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> would have to evaluate the availability of software and other factors before deciding when to sell the recorders in this country. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> asked the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION> to study an encoding system proposed by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> in which a narrow band in the upper mid-range frequencies is removed from a recording. A DAT recorder equipped with the anti-taping chip detects the `` notch'' and disables the machine's recording circuitry for a short period. The study found that the system is flawed because it does n't always work, the `` notch'' can sometimes be heard by listeners, and the system can be bypassed `` for about $ 100 by a competent electronics technician. `` It's like selling you a camera that wo n't take certain pictures,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>, director of the bureau's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, describing the encoding system. <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> said the effect of the notch on the recordings `` is subtle. Sometimes you can hear it and sometimes you ca n't.'' When the notch is discerned, it is often recognized as a missing note, he said. The bureau's testing team did n't study other anti-taping methods, he said. He added that while `` there are any number of ways'' of altering a recording to prevent copying, `` none of them is going to be fool proof.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recording </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> said the results of the study were a victory for the consumer and signals the end of the legislation before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The coalition has been fighting all anti-taping efforts as infringment on the rights of consumers to make recordings at home, for their private use, of records, tapes and compact discs. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Recording </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, questioned aspects of the study but said it virtually kills the CBS copy-code system `` as a viable political solution.'' But he said the recording industry remains committed to finding a solution through `` negotiation, legislation or litigation.'' <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> said his is a $ 5 billion a year industry that is losing $ 1.5 billion a year to home copying.
