<HEAD>Misuse of Auto Seat Belts Said Cutting Their Effectiveness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While the increasingly widespread use of automobile lap-shoulder belts is saving hundreds of lives, the belts often are misused in ways that reduce their effectiveness, a federal study concluded Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the most common abuse of the car safety belts is that they are worn too loosely or _ often in the case of children _ are tucked under the arm or back because of concern about the high angle of the harness. `` The lap-shoulder belts are very effective and achieve about all that can be expected of them if they are properly used,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>. `` But we have a lot of misuse and that problem has to be tackled.'' The safety board report is based on previous studies of seat belt use by other government agencies and the insurance industry as well as a detailed examination of 167 accidents in which at least one occupant wore a belt. <PERSON> Lynne </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, one of the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> staff investigators involved in the study, said the findings were not meant to be a random statistical sample, but that the data is `` consistent with the finding of widespread -LRB- belt -RRB- misuse.'' An examination of the accidents showed that 21 percent of the motorists were wearing belts too loosely, reducing their protection, the safety board said. It also cited an insurance industry study of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> motorists that put the estimate at about 25 percent. Ms. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said belts should be worn with no more than the width of a person's fist separating the belt from the body. The safety board urged the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to require that safety belts meet standards as to the maximum amount of slack allowed or require that the belt systems be equipped with a `` pre-tension'' device that automatically pulls a belt tight a split second before a crash. In addition, the examination of accident cases by the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> showed that 7 percent of the belt users had the shoulder harness portion of their belt routed improperly under an arm or behind their backs. Misuse of the belts was most prevelent among children, where one-third had belts not properly used. In some cases, children had belts routed under an arm or behind the back, two children were wearing a single belt or children wore belts with the seat in a reclining position, the report said. `` Such misuse ... seriously degrades the protective capabilities of the lap-shoulder belt, reducing it to a lap-only belt with inferior crash protection,'' the safety board said. Ironically, a number of auto safety pamphlets, including two distributed by the <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> and one by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, have advised parents to place the shoulder belt behind a child if the harness crosses the neck or face. `` The safety board does not agree,'' the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> report said. `` ... There is little evidence that small children or short adults are likely to be harmed by the shoulder portion of a ... belt.'' It said that in the accidents investigated it found no evidence `` that the shoulder ... belt induced more serious injuries to children than it prevented.'' The board called for the highway safety agency to revise its brochures. `` We have not had a chance to read -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> report -RRB- and have no comment at this time,'' <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON> said. Among the accidents, according to the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>, in which belt misuse had tragic results, were: _ A head-on crash in which a woman passenger, who had loosened her shoulder harness extensively, was killed Her husband, the driver, had worn his belt snugly and `` walked away from the crash with moderate injuries,'' said <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Stack </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> staff researcher. _ A crash in which a car struck a tree The driver, who had worn his belt properly, escaped with minor injuries while the passenger, whose shoulder belt was routed under her arm, was killed.
</TEXT>
