<HEAD>Carlucci Urges Lawmakers to Mute Criticism of NATO Allies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Reagan-Nato Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs lede to fix time element. Adds 5 grafs at end to UPDATE
with Senate hearing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s allies in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> should spend more money for defense, but congressional denunciations are n't the best way to get that done, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` I quite agree with the thesis that our allies need to do more,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. But he added that `` I do n't think it is very useful to simply berate the Europeans on this.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s comments came as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was heading for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to attend a two-day summit meeting of leaders of the 16-nation <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, D-Pa., the <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, criticized <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> nations for what he said was `` unequal sharing. He told <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> `` our allies in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> are not doing, in my estimation, enough for their own defense.'' Criticism of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has long been popular on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, where legislators have complained time and again that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> taxpayers are footing a disproportionate share of the alliance's defense bill. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is devoting about 6 percent of its gross national product to defense while no other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries spend a little more than 3 percent. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> agreed that `` we need to make every effort to get our allies to do more,'' but he said they now do more than is `` generally recognized.'' For example, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> supplies 90 percent of the ground troops which would be used to halt a Soviet attack. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s defense budget is 5.7 percent of the nation's GNP, not 6 percent, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. He also noted that American defense budgets have generally stayed even or declined in recent years. That was n't good enough for <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, who noted that the recent reductions came atop large increases in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first term. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has long set a target for each member to increase spending by 3 percent a year after inflation, and most nations do n't meet that target, <PERSON> Carluicci </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has n't met the 3 percent target for at least four years, he added. Both <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, told the committee that <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> needs to improve its conventional defenses in the wake of the treaty banning medium-range atomic missiles from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. That is similar to the message <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is carrying to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies and echoes a theme which the administration has been pushing since the treaty was signed Dec. 8 by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> detailed <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s shortcomings in non-nuclear weapons, but added, `` surely the prospect of having to fight 16 nations at once remains a sobering one for the Kremlin.'' `` But, put candidly, both the level of -LRB- nuclear -RRB- deterrence and the nuclear threshold remain too low,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> said. `` The chiefs have for a number of years consistently testified to that effect.'' `` It is essential for the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> members to correct'' the problems in non-nuclear weapons, he said. At the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> historian <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies `` ought to bear a larger share of the defense burden'' now that they have been rebuilt with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> help after World War II. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, author of the best-selling `` The Rise and Fall of Great Nations,'' said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should spurn protectionism and increase spending for basic technologies and for commercial research and development. <PERSON> Jeane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkpatrick </PERSON>, former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, agreed with <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies should bear more of the burden. But she criticized his view that there is a direct correlation between military spending and economic growth. Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the panel, noted that `` the help we gave and the protection we've given have helped <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> grow back into power Now, they are friendly competitors. But while they've taken us to the woodshed in international trade, we're the ones paying for the guards at the woodshed door.'' `` It seems to me we are draining our power trying to do too much,'' said <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>. `` Our adversaries are happy to see us try. Our allies have n't done as much as they can to help.''
