<HEAD>Record Low Number Spotted In Right Whale Survey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A record-low number of rare right whales was spotted during an annual survey off the coasts of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aquarium </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. An aquarium team that spent February surveying the right whale population in their popular wintering grounds detected only one mother-calf pair and five whales traveling separately. The total was three below the previous low of 10 in 1984, said aquarium researcher <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Kraus </PERSON>. The highest number spotted during the five years the survey has been conducted off the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> coasts was 26 in 1986, <PERSON> Kraus </PERSON> said. He said it was premature to speculate on reasons for the apparent decline in the right whale population in the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> waters, which are considered popular calving grounds. `` We do n't know whether the numbers are low because of a local problem that kept the whales away from that area,'' said <PERSON> Kraus </PERSON>. `` Or they may be somewhere down there and we are missing them.'' <PERSON> Kraus </PERSON> said there were reports the water temperature had been abnormally high this winter. But he said it was not clear if that caused the whales to winter elsewhere. The aquarium will match the winter survey numbers with those recorded next spring when the whales return to waters from <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>. That should help determine whether the right whale population has declined or if the whales chose a new location to spend the winter, <PERSON> Kraus </PERSON> said. The surveys have been conducted in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> waters for nine years and this was the fifth year of the survey off <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. The four prior surveys there have found right whales prefer to winter in waters five to 20 miles off the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> coast and within two miles of the beaches of <LOCATION> northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Right whales are considered the rarest of the large whale species. The worldwide right whale population is estimated at 2,500. It it is believed that 240 to 350 live in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. There are three types of right whales, which are known for their unusually large heads. The type found in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> are Black Right Whales, which have black bodies and sometimes with white areas on the belly. Black Right Whales grow up to 60 feet long.
