<HEAD>Defense Attacks Pilot's Credibitility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A defense attorney attacked the credibility of a pilot testifying Tuesday in the smuggling trial of <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON>, winning an admission that the man continued trafficking drugs while cooperating with the government. <PERSON> Leverett </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON>, 66, testified Monday that he made six cocaine flights in 1979. Those flights, made with admitted smuggler <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, are those listed in the indictment of <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, 38, and co-defendant <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, reputed to be one of the leaders of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s violent <ORGANIZATION> Medellin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cartel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> cocaine </ORGANIZATION> smugglers, is on trial on charges that he and others conspired to smuggle 3.3 tons of cocaine into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> via <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>'s Cay in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> from 1978 to 1980. Under cross-examination Tuesday by defense attorney <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> admitted he conducted other smuggling activity while we was cooperating with the government and testifying before a grand jury in 1980. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> is testifying under immunity from prosecution. He said he made flights to <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> for other people in 1980, bringing in either hashish or marijuana. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> pilot, bristled when <PERSON> Quinon </PERSON> used the word ` lie' when discussing inconsistent statements in his testimony and his grand jury appearances eight years ago. `` I do n't like the word, ` lie.' I looked it up in the dictionary last night and I suggest you do the same,'' he told <PERSON> Quinon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Quinon </PERSON> laboriously questioned <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> about his grand jury testimony in 1980 and many times Tuesday <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> said he could n't remember what he said in 1980 `` I'm sure the grand jury testimony as a whole is correct,'' <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise. <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pedro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, is charged only with being a part of the smuggling conspiracy. Defense attorneys and prosecutors got into several exchanges Tuesday out of the jury's presence. After one of a number of bench conferences with the judge, defense attorney <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> accused <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> of saying to him: `` You're going to sleaze yourself right into a hole, mister.'' <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> called <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>'s remarks `` patently offensive.'' <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>, however, argued that he made the comment to Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Ernst </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> and said: `` They're -LRB- defense attorneys -RRB- going to sleaze themselves into a hole.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> said he did n't plan to take any action and told the attorneys to present the exchange to a grievance committee if they desired to do so.
