<HEAD>Plan to Spend $6 Million on Pilots' Leather Jackets Draws Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> plan to spend $ 6.1 million on World War II-style leather jackets to boost flight crews' esprit de corps is drawing flak from civilians and retirees affected by budget cuts. `` I'm upset with this leather-jacket bit,'' <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Enyart </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> major who now lives in nearby <LOCATION> Fairview </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, said Tuesday. `` If we have to measure our patriotism by whether or not we have leather jackets, <PERSON> God </PERSON> help us, we're in trouble.'' About 280 of the 53,000 `` bomber'' jackets will go to flight crews with the <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>. `` To me it does n't reflect the professionalism of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Enyart </PERSON>, a former official of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a national organization that works to promote a strong national defense. `` It reflects a bunch of people wanting leather jackets,'' he said. The nation's armed services were ordered in November to slash 10 percent from their budgets for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> share of the reductions for the year amount to about $ 10.5 billion. Smaller custs were ordered for the current fiscal year. Critics say the jackets, which cost $ 115 each, are a prime example of waste. <PERSON> Enyart </PERSON> said he had received calls from about 20 people _ civilians as well as active and retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> personnel _ supporting his stance after local reports about his criticism of the jacket purchases during a time of budget austerity. Wide-ranging spending reductions throughout the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> include curtailment of equipment purchases and personnel cuts. Even retirees' medical benefits have been reduced, <PERSON> Enyart </PERSON> said. A hiring freeze has been in effect at <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> since Dec. 8, and last month, an undetermined number of temporary part-time civilian jobs were eliminated at <LOCATION> Scott </LOCATION>. On Tuesday, the base's command began offering voluntary early retirement to eligible civilian workers. The jacket purchases should be cut before jobs, said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Denton </PERSON>, an official of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>' Local R7-23, which represents about 3,000 civilian workers at <LOCATION> Scott </LOCATION>. `` It would seem to me that people putting hamburger on their table should come before they -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officials -RRB- put a new jacket on a pilot's back,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> sees it differently. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> plans to issue these flying jackets to primary crew members in order to enhance esprit de corps and to recognize the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s front-line pilots, navigators, weapons officers and enlisted crew members for their important contributions to the nation's defense,'' said a statement Tuesday from <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> officials at <LOCATION> Scott </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> plans to distribute the jackets to active and reserve forces. The jackets are to be purchased during the 1988 and 1989 fiscal years, officials say. Delivering them to flight crews is expected to take about a year, beginning in June.
