<HEAD>Swimming Likely to Continue At Historic Pond</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pond </LOCATION>, the retreat idealized by <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Thoreau </PERSON> in 1845, is at the center of a debate over whether it should be preserved or whether it should, as <PERSON> Thoreau </PERSON> wrote, `` belong to the public.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> declined Tuesday to adopt a bill that would ban swimming at <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, 15 miles west of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The bill would eliminate a manmade sand beach, restrict fishing and boating and require construction of sound barriers beside nearby roadways. Instead, committee members said they would consider expanding membership on the pond's citizen advisory panel. `` Fencing off <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pond </LOCATION> and banning swimming would be contrary to both the philosophy of <PERSON> Thoreau </PERSON> and the wishes of the owners who gave the property to the state,'' <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutensohn </PERSON> told the committee. `` I'm sure the Indians swam at <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pond </LOCATION>, I'm sure <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Thoreau </PERSON> swam at <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pond </LOCATION> and I'm sure the people of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> should,'' <PERSON> Gutensohn </PERSON> said. The chief opponent of continued recreation at <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, did not attend the hearing though the legislation was sponsored by her group, <ORGANIZ