 the pond unrecognizable to its 19th-century admirers. `` Anytime you have a first-class resource you have a threat of overuse,'' said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinreb </PERSON>, the state's project manager for the pond. In the 13 years that the DEM has controlled <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION>, the state has spent $ 2 million on projects to upgrade and preserve the site. Another $ 500,000 has been set aside for restoring the banks of the pond. <PERSON> Gutensohn </PERSON> said the money will cover about half of the restoration job. In addition, the state plans to limit parking around the pond to keep down summertime attendance.
