<HEAD>U.S. Says Iran-Iraq Missile Attacks Increase Need for Arms Embargo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration on Tuesday called attacks on Iranian and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> cities a dangerous development in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war and adds `` a new urgency'' to <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> work on an arms embargo designed to force a truce. <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, condemned the missile raids and said they represent `` a serious escalation of the Iran-Iraq war.'' `` Attacks on civilians achieve no military end,'' she said. `` They fuel the psychology of hatred which is responsible for continuing this destructive conflict.'' <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said Tuesday it fired 16 missiles into <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. It was the first long-range rocket attack on the Iranian capital since the war began in September 1980. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said 27 civilians were killed. The official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> hit <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> with two missiles late Tuesday night, killing or wounding an unspecified number of civilians. Last July, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> adopted resolution 598 calling for a truce in the war and pledging to impose an arms embargo against either party that refused to heed the call. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has said it would accept a cease-fire but <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has declined to go along and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been pressing the world body to impose the weapons ban on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. `` We believe adoption of an arms embargo resolution to enforce 598 has taken a new urgency with the renewal of the war of the cities,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. `` We urge all members of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to act on this now, without further delay, particularly permament members who have special responsibilities to provide leadership,'' she said. She was referring to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, said another <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, speaking on condition of anonymity. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> offered a compromise last week in an effort to satisfy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demands for quick passage of a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and meet a Soviet desire for more diplomacy by <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, the official said. It would permit immediate passage of an embargo followed by a 30-day delay in implementation and another peace effort by <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>. The official said that in response to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure to accept the compromise, the Soviet envoy to the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Belonogov </PERSON> has said he is awaiting a decision from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. On March 1, the rotating chairmanship of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> will pass from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said an arms embargo `` will make it more difficult for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to pursue the war,'' but will not mean an end to the conflict if <LOC