ome families were refused for emigration because they do not have close enough relatives in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, which `` fully contradicted'' what Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> told him last month in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told reporters Feb. 22, after meeting with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, that the Soviet minister promised `` flexibility'' in applying rules that require applicants to have close relatives abroad. He said <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> also told him `` categorically'' that the only barrier to emigration is past work involving state secrets. Many people whom the government alleges were exposed to state secrets say they saw the information years or decades ago and that it does not compromise the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` I last worked in atomic science 22 years ago and they are refusing me because of that reason even today,'' <PERSON> Kislik </PERSON> said. He added that the officials indicated they would meet with the Jews again to discuss the cases of 20 Soviet Jews who have heart conditions, cancer or other ailments and who want to leave. `` We also gave them a list of people from 60 to 82 years old who want to emigrate,'' he said. In February, Soviet authorities allowed 723 Jews to emigrate, according to the Geneva-based agency that helps the emigrants resettle. That was a slight increase from the January total of 658. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Intergovernmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Migration </ORGANIZATION>, Jewish emigration from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> last year reached 8,011, its highest level since 1981.
