<HEAD>British Mail to be Postmarked `Jesus is Alive!'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 4 grafs SUB for 16th graf pvs, Post Office ... UPDATING with
humanist protest, U.S. outlook, edits to tighten. Picks up 17th
graf pvs, Slennet, 41 ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Post Office on Tuesday began postmarking nearly all letters mailed in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> with the words `` Jesus is Alive!'' as part of a private arrangement financed by an evangelist. Jewish leaders criticized the Christian cancellation as potentially offensive. The special postmark, which also contains a small cross, will last six weeks and was paid for by <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Slennet </PERSON>, who sells religious literature at two bookstores in <LOCATION> Southend-on-Sea </LOCATION>, east of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. He said <PERSON> God </PERSON> told him to buy the postmark. The state-owned Post Office said <PERSON> Slennet </PERSON> paid the equivalent of $ 88,500 for the privilege of having every letter mailed through 68 of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 69 sorting offices stamped `` Jesus is Alive!'' The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> has adopted various methods of boosting revenue under Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservative government, which believes that state-owned services should pay for themselves. Receiving the postmark will be all mail _ including that sent abroad _ excluding parcels, periodicals and those letters stamped by businesses that have their own franking facilities. Nearly 52 million letters are mailed daily in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. `` The printing of this slogan in no way confirms <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> approval of its contents,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>. `` The slogan is not considered to be contentious.'' <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, spokesman for Lord <PERSON> Jakobovits </PERSON>, the chief rabbi of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, said his office was `` flooded with phone calls'' after news of the slogan appeared in newspapers Tuesday. `` We recognize that this is a Christian country and we have the utmost respect for the primacy for the church,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said in an interview. However, `` we do fear that the slogan that will be carried is by implication addressed to non-Christians and could well cause offense and resentment. We've made our feelings known to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. Rabbi <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON>, chairman of the Assembly of Rabbis of the <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Britain </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` This country allows me freedom of religion, and an official organization should not have accepted such a commission that will infringe not only upon my rights but the rights of other non-Christians.'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said his office was aware of `` a number of complaints.'' Asked if these had caused any change of heart, he said: `` I've had no indication of that.'' He said no complaints had been received from other non-Christian groups. However, the British <ORGANIZATION> Humanist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a national association for the non-religious, said the decision showed `` insensitive disregard'' for other beliefs. `` Imagine the furor if we had asked to have ` <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> is Dead' printed on hundreds of millions of letters,'' said association spokesman <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Horwood </PERSON> He said he is writing the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> asking that the postmark be withdrawn. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> official said the chance of something similar in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was unlikely. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Rustin </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Stamp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Branch </ORGANIZATION>, said limits are strict on special cancellations and religious messages are excluded. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Post Office regulations require paid messages to be `` non-controversial, non-political and likely to be generally acceptable to the public,'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Slennet </PERSON>, 41, said he got the idea five years ago listening to a sermon in which the preacher talked about collecting stamps and postmarks. `` The Lord has since confirmed to me in various ways that this is the right thing to do,'' he said in an interview. `` In 1986 that small quiet voice we hear when <PERSON> God </PERSON> speaks said ` postmark'.'' He said that he has informed Christian groups around the country of his idea and received contributions toward paying for it. Slennet belongs to Intercessors for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, an evangelical organization. He said the slogan was chosen in the spirit of Easter. The <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> is n't printing the slogan because it already had been booked for one commemorating <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588.
