<HEAD>Government Moves To Bar Foreign Funds For Anti-Apartheid Groups</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf pvs, The new ... to include
right-wing groups probably not affected. Picks up 6th graf pvs,
Another section ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government Tuesday proposed a bill to outlaw foreign funding of political activity, a move that could cripple anti-apartheid groups and churches thus far spared from the new crackdown on opposition. No court challenge of the restrictions would be allowed. Last week, the government banned 18 predominantly black organizations from political activity, including the largest anti-apartheid coalition and largest labor federation. Leading anti-apartheid clergymen vowed Tuesday _ before the new bill was introduced _ that the churches would take over some of the programs of the banned groups and more aggressively confront the government. The new legislation, called `` The Promotion of Orderly Politics Bill,'' would prohibit all organizations from receiving money from abroad for political purposes and would empower the justice minister to seize foreign funds received by certain groups. His powers would be indefinitely retroactive. The foreign funds provision was not expected to hurt right-wing organizations, which receive most of their money from donations from within <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. However, another section of the bill could apply to right-wing white supremacist groups that oppose the government's limited apartheid reforms. It sets a penalty of two years in jail or a fine of about $ 2,000 for anyone who `` says or does anything'' to foment hostility or violence between different racial, cultural or religious groups. The penalties would apply to anyone who displays a banner, emblem or slogan deemed to convey such hostility, and also to anyone who attends a gathering where such items are displayed. The South African Council of Churches, which includes most major Protestant denominations and is engaged in civil rights work, has received more than 90 percent of its funds from abroad in recent years. The <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> cooperates with the council of churches but receives substantial overseas funds separately. The Rev. <PERSON> Smangiliso </PERSON> <PERSON> Mkhatshwa </PERSON>, secretary-general of the Southern African <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, said the bill might be difficult to enforce. `` If the church says supporting the families of detainees and paying legal fees is the work of love, the work of evangelism, it is difficult to see how the government can define for the church what is pastoral and what is political,'' he said. In Parliament, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON>, veteran member of the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, condemned the arrests Monday of prominent clergymen who were protesting the government crackdown. About 25 church leaders, including Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, and 125 other protesters were detained briefly after riot policeman blocked them from marching to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> with a petition protesting the bans on opposition groups. After the most prominent clergymen were placed in police vehicles, a water cannon was sprayed on the other protesters, who were kneeling and singing hymns. Mrs. <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON> said Tuesday police should have allowed the march to proceed, `` thus avoiding all that sensational publicity that has resulted in adverse headlines across the world and has added further fuel to the campaign for sanctions. This government has a death wish.'' Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said the clergymen had defied a request to disperse and `` scandalously provoked'' police. `` We have to once again take the blame for the misconduct of people who hide behind the cloth of sanctimony,'' he said. One of the arrested churchmen, Roman Catholic Archibishop <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Naidoo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, said in an interview Tuesday that he and his colleagues considered it their duty to intensify the churches' challenge of the government. `` There is going to be in this country a continuing moral confrontation,'' he said. He predicted the authorities would deal cautiously with defiant clergymen because `` they are intelligent enough to realize they are dealing here with a great moral force ... and the moral sensibilities of people all over the world.'' The government has backed off before in the face of concerted church resistance, the last time in 1986 when many of the same ministers arrested Monday had gathered at <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> George </LOCATION>'s Anglican Cathderal to defy a ban on calling for the release of detainees The prohibition was not enforced and was dropped from the next issue of emergency regulations. The Rev. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, dean of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> George </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION>, said it was significant that no one in Monday's march had been charged and all were freed without bail. `` I think they're embarrassed by this; they do n't want to put archbishops in jail. But they make their own nooses for their own necks.''
