<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Tuesday gave the three major television networks the go-ahead to take exit polls at <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> voting places during the Super Tuesday presidential preference primaries next week. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> had sued state and <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> election officials to stop enforcement of a 1985 law prohibiting exit polls or public opinion surveys within 250 feet of a polling place. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> Tuesday issued a preliminary injunction stopping the state from enforcing the new law beyond 25 feet of buildings in which polling places are located. The ruling, which came after a hearing on the lawsuit Monday, allows the networks to conduct the exit polls during the March 8 primaries, as long as their poll takers are stationed no closer than 25 feet from the door. Hall indicated he would rule later on the networks' contention that the law violates the Constitution's First Amendment guarantee of freedom of speech and of the press. While the state `` has a legitimate interest in protecting the ` sanctity of the polling place,''' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> wrote in Tueday's ruling, it appears the 250 foot prohibition on exit polls `` is not ` narrowly tailored' to accomplish that goal in the ` least restrictive means available,''' as required by previous court rulings on free speech issues. A more limited ban, keeping exit pollers out of polling places and 25 feet away from their doors, `` would likely satisfy even the most rigorous constitutional scrutiny,'' he wrote. `` We're delighted by the results,'' said <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, an attorney representing the networks. `` It will make it possible for more people to have more information more quickly about the election results and their meaning on Super Tuesday.'' <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, the assistant secretary of state in charge of elections, said Tuesday that copies of the judge's order will be sent to county election officials for relay to their precinct managers before the primaries next week. In exit polling, survey takers ask a random sample of voters leaving the polling place to fill out a written list of questions about whom they voted for and what issues are important to them, as well as such information as their age, sex and economic status. During testimony in Monday's hearing, <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitofsky </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>' election and survey unit, testified that exit polls are by far the most accurate and the quickest way to gauge what groups of people are voting for which candidate. But, he said, the 250-foot distance limitation effectively banned public opinion surveys of people leaving polling places because the surveyor is too far away from the exit to be able to intercept the voters randomly. The law had been enacted because elections officials, mostly in metropolitan <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, had complained that exit poll takers intimidated voters, according to testimony from former state Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Bray </PERSON>, who chaired the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> when it considered the measure.
