<HEAD>BBC Says Government Drops Objections to Program on Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday the government has withdrawn its objections to a radio program that included interviews with intelligence officials. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government won a court order in December preventing the broadcasting of the first program in the planned three-part series, `` My Country: Right or Wrong.'' The government argued that the series, dealing with the tug of war between state secrecy and freedom of information, could harm national security. Publicly funded <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> said the series portrays the work of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s intelligence agencies and did not reveal anything an enemy could not already know. The government withdrew its objections to the program after its lawyers received a transcript of it from the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION>, the company said. The second and third programs have yet to be recorded. `` I am glad that we will be able to transmit this program,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Birt </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy director general. `` I am only sorry it has been long delayed.'' He did not say when the program will be broadcast. The High Court judge who approved the gag order had said the government was properly concerned that nine former and serving intelligence officials interviewed for the series may have broken their oaths of secrecy. <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleary </PERSON> said Tuesday night: `` The <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> initially refused to turn over the transcripts to the government, arguing that would amount to pre-censorship. But the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> later, during the legal process, had to provide the transcripts as part of its defense evidence.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservative government had used the argument of lifetime confidentiality by security agents to prevent the publication in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> of `` Spycatcher,'' a book by former agent <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, who now lives in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. The book has been published in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
