<HEAD>Senator Questions Handling of Attorney General's Stock Profits</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 21st graf bgng: A telephone ... with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with comment from Chinn's attorney. Picks up 22nd graf pvs bgng:
Chinn was ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>'s investment manager allocated stock-trading profits to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s brokerage accounts under a procedure that a senator said Tuesday raises questions of `` possible financial favors or gifts'' to the Cabinet member. In a report by its Democratic majority staff, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee on Oversight of Government Management said stock trader <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> pooled <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s money with that of several other customers in 1985 and 1986 and, after completing stock trades, assigned profits or losses to the attorney general's account The report said it appears that in seven instances, <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> allocated stock trades to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s account in amounts exceeding the balance available in the account to pay for those trades. In the seven instances, the amount of the stock trades exceeded the balances in <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s account by $ 5,000 to $ 140,000. <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> turned a profit of nearly $ 40,000 for <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> on a $ 50,000 investment in just 23 stock trades over a 19-month span. <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s longtime friend who is under indictment in the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> scandal, in five of the trades was one of the customers whose money was pooled with that of the attorney general. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> introduced <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> to <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON>, who became the attorney general's financial adviser in May 1985. <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> `` was n't investing Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s money, as much as he was assigning profits and losses to the accounts of Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and his other clients at his own discretion,'' Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., the subcommittee's chairman, said in a letter to the Office of Government Ethics <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON>'s `` assignment of stock transactions retroactively to those accounts appears to have no relationship to the amount of money in those accounts,'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> continued. `` Because he did not allocate winners and losers to his clients' accounts until after the fact, he was effectively able to assign greater benefits to some _ including apparently Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> on numerous occasions. The procedure `` raises questions about possible financial favors or gifts, about possible conflict of interest, -LRB- and -RRB- about the judgment of the attorney general in being involved in a partnership with a director of a company -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- with Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> had directly assisted when he was working in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> as counselor to the president,'' said <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> asked the ethics office for a formal finding as to whether <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> has complied with federal regulations governing gifts and loans to public officials and whether he has violated an executive order prohibiting the appearance of a conflict of interest. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Korten </PERSON> said the issues raised by <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> were matters that had been fully examined in congressional hearings last July and that now are before the independent counsel studying <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s dealings with <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>. He said it would be inappropriate for the ethics office to get involved at this point. `` What Senator <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> is trying to do is wrap an 8-month old fish in today's paper,'' <PERSON> Korten </PERSON> said. `` All we have here is a highly partisan effort to grab another headline on this thing and keep the <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> pot boiling.'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> has acknowledged interceding on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> when the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, defense contractor was seeking a $ 32 million, no-bid contract to build small engines for the Army. Within months of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s intercession, <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> was awarded the work. The report said that in one instance, <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> bought and sold 5,000 shares of a new stock issue in <ORGANIZATION> Oliver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> worth $ 30,000 on Feb. 11, 1986. It was n't until the next day, however, that <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> instructed <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> where one of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s accounts was established, that 2,000 of the shares were to be recorded for <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s account. The transaction gave <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> a profit of more than $ 1,700. In another instance, on Sept. 12, 1985, <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> allocated a purchase of $ 80,000 worth of stock in <ORGANIZATION> Rockefeller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Properties </ORGANIZATION> to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s account at the brokerage house of Bear, <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON> at a time when the account had a balance of only $ 51,000. The trade resulted in a profit of nearly $ 900. In a third instance, <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> bought and sold <ORGANIZATION> Firemans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock on Oct. 23, 1985. It was n't until mid-afternoon of the day he bought and sold it that <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> directed that 2,000 of the shares be assigned to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s account. That transaction earned <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> more than $ 900. <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> assigned purchases to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s and his other customers' accounts `` after it was known whether the purchase would yield a profit or loss. `` It appears that Mr. <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> was able to decide just which of his clients would get profits and which would get losses,'' the senator said in his letter to the ethics office. One of <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON>'s lawyers, <PERSON> Cristina </PERSON> <PERSON> Arguedas </PERSON>, said that her client's stock trading has been examined at length by independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, who is conducting a criminal investigation of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>. She said the independent counsel has found no wrongdoing in connection with the stock trading. One of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s attorneys, <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>, said the attorney general had set up a limited blind partnership with <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON>'s company under which <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was kept unaware of any of the details of <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON>'s stock trading <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> lost money on five of the 23 stock transactions. <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> was indicted Dec. 22 with longtime <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> friend <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> and a business associate, <ORGANIZATION> R. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kent </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, on racketeering, fraud and conspiracy charges in an alleged scheme to extract payments from <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> in order to influence <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and other federal officials. All three have pleaded innocent. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s involvement with <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> has been under criminal investigation by independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> since last May 11. The attorney general has denied wrongdoing.
