<HEAD>Judge Lifts Texas Ban of Florida Citrus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Tuesday overturned the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> ban on <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus fruit, and state officials began planning their next legal move against regulations allowing the shipments. The ban was imposed last month ban after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> lifted a 3 -LCB- - year-old federal quarantine on <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus that was prompted by outbreaks of citrus canker in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> agriculture officials said the ban was necessary to protect <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' $ 65 million-a-year citrus industry from canker. The state now plans to seek an injunction against new federal rules that allow shipment of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus meeting certain standards to other citrus-producing states, said <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodfin </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Nowlin </PERSON> said Tuesday that he lifted the state ban, imposed last month after the new federal rule took effect, because the federal regulation took precedence over the state rule. The ban was due to end March 12, when <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> officials planned to have gathered information on the federal rule and take some permanent action. `` We feel we need to do whatever we can to protect the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> citrus industry,'' <PERSON> Woodfin </PERSON> said. The injunction request will charge that the federal rule was issued abruptly and did not allow sufficient time to study its possible effects, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citrus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION>, a growers association, and <ORGANIZATION> Tuxedo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> shipper and grower, sued <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> last month to stop the emergency state quarantine. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> and Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> joined the court action. The lawsuit called the ban unconstitutional and invalid. It said the action would mean a loss of millions of dollars to the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus industry. `` We expected this decision,'' <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> said. `` Federal rules and regulations supersede state rules and regulations as it pertains to plant matters. The law's a little different between plant and animal.'' Canker, which can seriously damage citrus plants and fruit, was found in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in 1984. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> officials said <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> producers must meet strict standards under the new federal regulation in order to ship fruit to citrus-producing states, including <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON>, chief of the bureau of pest eradication for the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said he had never heard of canker being found on mature citrus fruit that was ready to be shipped. It would be difficult to transmit canker from fruit to citrus groves, he said.
