<HEAD>Chancellor Raises Possibility Of New Elections Over Tax Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The coalition government of Socialists and conservatives, already under strain because of the <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> affair, could collapse over tax reform, according to comments by Chancellor <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON> on Tuesday. The coalition has been strained for months over President <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s World War II activities, and <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON> said again Tuesday he would consider resigning if that issue continued to affect his government's work. But Socialist <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON>, speaking with reporters after a Cabinet session, dealt mainly with tax legislation. He said it was possible he would meet again this week with Vice Chancellor <PERSON> Alois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mock </PERSON> in a last-ditch effort to reach agreement on tax reform. Mock is chairman of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Austrian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, running as the conservative candidate, won the presidential election in June 1986. The term for the mainly titular presidency is for six years, and <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has rejected critics' demands that he resign <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON> said the question of new elections `` would lie close at hand'' if the tax dispute is not resolved. The last parliamentary elections were held on Nov. 23, 1986, for four-year terms. <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON> was asked about early elections and he said, `` I do not seek them but I do not shy away from them either.'' Mock and <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON> have had several inconclusive meetings on the proposed tax reform. The Socialists insist that a major gap in the budget can not be filled without imposing a tax on savings deposit interest. The conservatives strongly oppose such a tax. Some political observers have said the combined tax dispute and controversy over <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> may be too much for the coalition to survive. <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON>, criticizing <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, said it was not enough for the president to keep restating his position. He said <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> would have to contribute to resolving the crisis over his presidency `` in word and deed,'' but added he did not want to elaborate. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> served as a lieutenant in the German army in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> during World War II. The World Jewish Congress and other groups say he was involved with army units that deported thousands of Jews and other people from the area to Nazi labor or death camps. An international commission of six historians, appointed by the Austrian government to investigate <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s past, said he was `` in close proximity'' to some Nazi atrocities in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> and knew they were going on but made no attempt to prevent them. The report, released last month, did not support allegations that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> was involved in atrocities. But it left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general, has repeatedly denied any wrongdoings during the war.
