<HEAD>Federal Judge Fines Seven Church Members in Child Labor Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge ruled Tuesday that two companies who used young people in a church job-training program had violated child-labor laws and ordered stiff penalties for seven people who ran the program. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> threatened to fine the seven $ 21,000 a day if they continued to use the children, as young as 9 years old. He wrote that the children were `` manifestly being exploited.'' <ORGANIZATION> Shiloh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> True </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> members acknowledged during the January trial that their children worked at construction sites and in shops where they carried bricks, laid foundations and more recently, operated forklifts and power saws. They said they had been doing so for at least 100 years. <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> ordered <ORGANIZATION> McGee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> to pay $ 98,225 in back wages plus nearly $ 36,000 in interest. <PERSON> McGee </PERSON> <PERSON> Brothers </PERSON> and co-defendant <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Woodworking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Mint </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> also were ordered to pay nearly $ 70,000 in court costs. Spokesmen for the companies were not immediately available for comment. There was no answer at the company offices, and their lawyers were not in their offices. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> said they had not received a copy of the decision and could not comment on whether the $ 21,000-per-day fine was retroactive to Oct. 5, when <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> issued an order to stop using the children. `` The minors are clearly dependent on the defendants' business for their employment and are the class of person whom the act is designed to protect,'' <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> wrote in a 58-page opinion. `` They are manifestly being exploited by defendants in this case, whether or not they proclaim their purpose to be in furtherance of their religious beliefs,'' <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> wrote. When the owners of the companies, both church members, continued the program for the church after <PERSON> Potter </PERSON>'s October order, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> asked they be found in contempt of the injunction and be fined $ 20,000 a day. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> said <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON>'s would be fined $ 5,000 per day and its two owners, <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> and <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, be fined $ 500 each per day thay they remained in contempt of his order. The judge ordered <ORGANIZATION> McGee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> to pay $ 10,000 per day and order five brothers who owned the company to pay $ 1,000 each per day that they remained in contempt of the order.
