<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> appeared ready on Tuesday night to resume his diplomatic shuttle in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> after reporting to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> told <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> at a three-hour meeting in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> earlier Tuesday that he was interested in <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s effort to set up <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> negotiations. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> did not directly endorse the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> initiative, but told <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> he appreciated the effort being made to open talks. `` It was a serious discussion, covering the whole waterfront,'' the official said. `` Nobody is saying yes or no.'' A statement issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Jordanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> reiterated <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s position that an international peace conference should be attended by the five permanent members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ and `` all parties to the conflict, including the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> arranged to confer with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> briefly Tuesday night and more fully on Wednesday before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> begins his talks in the Belgian capital with 15 other allied leaders attending a <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> summit. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> would return to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> at the conclusion of the summit Thursday night and try over the next two days to get acceptance of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> formula for negotiations to deal with both Palestinian unrest in areas under Israeli control and an overall Arab-Israeli settlement. `` He's a key, in my opinion,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> before their meeting at the king's residence in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION> district. `` He has immense standing and is a person who has been here a long time.'' Talking to reporters on the way to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> acknowledged he made little progress in four days of shuttle diplomacy. He said he could detect a narrowing of differences, but `` I do n't know if I could describe them in any way that would be perceptible to anyone else.'' Yet, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, `` assuming everyone continues the attitude they have to keep working, to keep working, we'll do it.'' President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, however, in his first comment on his talks with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, said Tuesday he had reservations about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan and he would disclose them only after a final formula was reached. <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> conferred in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> Sunday. <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> spoke to reporters while visiting neighboring <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN