he <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had persuaded <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to relax restrictions in permitting two Palestinians, <PERSON> Hanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Siniora </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> editor, and <PERSON> Fayez </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahme </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> lawyer, to go to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to meet with him five weeks ago. `` We have communicated with them in some important, substantive ways,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> approaches to the Palestinians. He said he had got the Palestinians' reaction indirectly while in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. `` It is n't as though there's no feedback, `` <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` There is feedback. It's not a substitute for directly sitting down with people, and that in a sense is what we've been calling for all along. In the end we've got to sit down together, so we have made a major effort to communicate with them.'' A group of 15 Palestinians invited to meet with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> Friday did not show up under <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> orders. He was similarly snubbed in October on a trip to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>.
