<HEAD>Public Quarrel Of Bishops Seen As Eroding Their Joint Influence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s doctrinal umpire was asked at a recent <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> news conference whether current controversy among American bishops might weaken their collective voice, he would n't say However, the question is regarded a potentially more underlying threat to the bishops' joint influence than the surface cause of their present public quarrel _ a statement on AIDS. Cardinal <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratzinger </PERSON>, a powerful dispenser of church discipline, said only that he would n't talk about the matter until he speaks with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bishops about it this spring. He has been critical of organizations of bishops such as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION>, and he left hanging the potential of <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> intervention of some kind. The bishops' unusual out-in-the-open dispute _ over an AIDS statement issued by the bishops' 50-member administrative board in mid-December _ has focused on some content of the statement itself. But several knowledgeable churchmen saw in the conflict a potential erosion of the bishops' collective teaching function via their conference, which has become increasingly vigorous on issues from economics to nuclear weaponry. `` The loser will be the bishops' conference itself,'' writes Monsignor <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Basler </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tablet </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> sociologist <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> says the controversy `` plays into the hands of people who question the purpose and effectiveness of the national conference's collegiality. Collegiality, the mutually shared responsibility of bishops and others, was stressed by the reforming <ORGANIZATION> Second </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> of 1962-65, and has been manifested increasingly in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bishops' joint teaching documents <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, author of numerous books on church developments, including his study of the growing scope of the conference, `` Re-Imagining American Catholicism,'' said in an interview: `` If personalities begin to speak outside the conference and indicate that the conference wishes do not match their own, then the harm to the conference could be irreparable.'' Asked if that was happening, he said, `` Exactly.'' He said it `` would please certain people in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> who have long been suspicious and wary of the bishops' conference in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. There are several Curial officials who wish to diminish its influence on a practical level.'' <PERSON> Ratzinger </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s watchful Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, has said there is `` no theological basis'' for national bishops' conferences. He says such organizations risk smothering <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s direct line of authority with individual bishops. That authority plainly can be more readily exercised with lone bishops than with national blocs of them. In any case, those objecting to the AIDS statement have been largely those regarded as among the bishops' conservative wing, tending to be more closely aligned with the conservative <PERSON> Ratzinger </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said he presumed `` good motives'' of those challenging the AIDS statement, but `` the effect is to damage the process of collegiality itself.'' `` Collegiality is the process used to avoid seeming personality conflicts,'' he said. `` Collegiality means everybody is heard, with a focus on the issue, rather than on two or three personalities.'' Individual bishops always are free to dissent from conference conclusions, but a highly inclusive consensus usually is achieved, and any bishops disagreeing simply disregard the recommendations in their dioceses, rather than challenging the process. In the present conflict, several bishops, notably <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s Cardinal <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Law </PERSON>, have publicly assailed the AIDs document Several others, including <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s Cardinal <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardin </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>'s Archbishop <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pilarczyk </PERSON>, have defended it. The document repeatedly insists on the church's teaching of abstinence from sex before marriage and fidelity within marriage as the only sure safeguards against AIDS, saying that without them, there is no such thing as `` safe sex.'' But one paragraph caused the fuss. It says public educational programs, directed at people who may reject church standards, could include information about condoms, which some medical experts say may help prevent AIDS. Critics charged this implied approving condoms, condemned by the church as birth-control devices. Defenders insist the document does not approve condoms, but saw them as a `` lesser evil'' compared to the `` greater evil'' of spreading a deadly disease. The bishops' administrative board meets March 21 to consider the furor, and may put it before the entire conference of bishops in June. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Ratzinger </PERSON> said he would discuss it with bishops in their ad limina -LRB- periodic -RRB- visits to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> beginning in March. The bishops' conference first was formed in 1917 to coordinate church efforts in World War I. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> threatened to supress it in 1922 on grounds it infringed on jurisdiction of individual bishops. The bishops managed to preserve it, insisting it was a voluntary organization, depending on each bishop's free choice to participate, and by their consensus, exercised collective responsibilities and moral suasion. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conference has inspired 42 similar national <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops' conferences around the world, acting to carry out mutual responsibilities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs, March 4</NOTE>
