 Roman Catholic, <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> representatives have urged the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to ratify, without amendments or delay, the U.S.-Soviet treaty for reducing intermediate-range nuclear forces. The Rev. <PERSON> Arie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, including most major <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> and Eastern Orthodox bodies, called the treaty a `` first step toward developing real security for us and the world's people.'' Roman Catholic Archbishop <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahony </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angles </LOCATION>, head of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bishops' international policy committee, said the treaty should become part of a continuing process of disarmament, making for more stable Soviet-U.S. relationships. The religious leaders testified before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Relations Committee.
