 Despite the anguish of American Jews over the current violence in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, their commitment to the Jewish state has not been weakened, says a veteran observer of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> scene. <PERSON> Hyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Bookbinder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> special representative, told a conference sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jews have felt `` agony, anguish, frustration _ even anger at times.'' But he added: `` It would be a serious mistake to interpret these reactions as rejection of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> or even a dilution of commitment.''
