<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Roman Catholic worshipers in this diocese _ and others across the country _ last weekend took home a little cardboard piece that folds into a small `` bowl.'' During the Lenten season between now and Easter, they're asked to place in the `` bowl'' each week the cost of a small meal _ the accumulated proceeds of which go to feed the hungry. Called `` Operation Rice Bowl,'' the program is sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, with 75 percent of the total collected going to world-wide relief, and 25 percent of it retained to help the local poor. <LOCATION> Youngstown </LOCATION> Bishop <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> said the project is an excellent means of observing the Lenten practice of almsgiving and `` adds an element of awareness of the hunger that others suffer.''
