<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: A Can-Do Conductor in a Can-Do Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON>, who has been the music director of the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> since 1985, is as delighted with the orchestra as he is with the city itself. Just before <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> from his previous orchestra in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> philanthropist <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyerhoff </PERSON>, who'd been picking up the symphony's bills, died. `` To my horror, we had an accumulated deficit of $ 2.3 million and we were losing $ 1 million a year. We would be out of business in a year unless we raised money,'' he said. A new executive director and the board, with some new members, were told by consultants they probably could n't raise a $ 14 million endowment. `` They went out and raised $ 40 million in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> in 22 months _ a new world's record. `` It was done by business leaders, which is essentially the way it has to be done. The selling point was, if you want to have a city that's taken seriously, we have to have an orchestra,'' <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON> said. `` <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> had a renaissance in the last 15 years. It's a can-do town. People who live there feel they can do what they want to do. `` We did a tour of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> last May. One of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>'s banks paid for it. The governor and a senator came along. They did a presentation lunch in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, with a big slide show. Orchestra musicians played. People were invited to our concert the next night.'' The year's tour for the orchestra started March 7 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. It will continue in <LOCATION> Davis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, with cellist Yo-Yo Ma as guest. Next year, the orchestra will tour the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> with flute soloist <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Galway </PERSON>. This season, <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON> started Saturday morning `` informal concerts,'' repeats of Friday night concerts with a top price of $ 9 and a little conversation. `` They said, ` You have to talk to the audience.' I'm a fan of ` Prairie Home Companion.' I decided to do it like an old radio show,'' <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON> said. `` We have a phony sponsor _ tapioca _ and a tapioca jingle. Next year we'll do eight of them, broadcast live by <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>. I explain the musical themes for them to follow while they listen. We recommend that little kids do n't come; it's serious classical music with zaniness in between pieces. `` I'm an American. I'm not Viennese. I have wild ideas and fantasies. Why not let them loose when you have the chance?'' This season, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> is broadcasting 13 regular symphony concerts and the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is doing several. After the tour, <PERSON> Ma </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> will record <PERSON> Britten </PERSON>'s `` Symphony for Cello and Orchestra'' and <PERSON> Barber </PERSON>'s `` Cello Concerto'' for CBS. The orchestra has made a <ORGANIZATION> Berlioz </ORGANIZATION> album for Telarc and an album by resident composer <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Rouse </PERSON> for Nonesuch. Telarc plans to record the Schumann symphonies and an all-Elgar compact disc with the Baltimore Symphony. `` I work with my orchestra a lot,'' the 51-year-old conductor said. `` My contract calls for 20 weeks a year. I do about 24. The days are over when I want to flit about, guest conducting. `` I want to make the <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> into a great orchestra. In order to do that you have to spend time digging in the garden. You ca n't just smell the flowers You have to make them grow; you have to be there. Guest conducting does n't do much for you musically. What really does a lot for you is to work with your orchestra to develop a repertoire and a style of playing that is uniquely your own. You really then get to make the music you're capable of making. `` With guesting, you're doing pieces you know pretty well. You come in like a lover, smile, make love and go away. It's a little like the singles scene. When you're with the wife, you really have to be there for the long haul.'' The conductor's family includes a son who has a synthesizer business, a daughter in a <LOCATION> Brisbane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, dance company and a 12-year-old son living with <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON> and his wife in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> native, met the late <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Monteux </PERSON>, conductor of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Symphony who was then 83, at <LOCATION> Tanglewood </LOCATION> one summer. Three years later, <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON> began to assist him. `` He was a great model to emulate,'' <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON> said. `` He was a master of balance and was at home in all styles of music. He had a great tradition behind him. He'd played in a string quartet for <PERSON> Brahms </PERSON>. He conducted <PERSON> Diaghilev </PERSON>'s ballets, including the first ` Rite of Spring.' He was a warm human being who got along with orchestra musicians. He was a psychologist and had wonderful patience.'' At the 1983 <ORGANIZATION> Holland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Monteux </PERSON> recommended <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON> to the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> Chamber Orchestra when a scheduled conductor got sick. From that, <PERSON> Zinman </PERSON> became music director of the <ORGANIZATION> Netherlands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION> from 1964 -77 and of the <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION> Philharmonic from 1979-82. He was the <PERSON> Rochester </PERSON> <PERSON> Philharmonic </PERSON>'s music director from 1974-85. Someday he'd like to help young conductors. `` I would like to take three pupils, use them as assistants and coach them. It's a question of finding a way to schedule that and get the money to do it,'' he said. `` I really believe you must pay back what you've borrowed.''
