<HEAD>Books and Authors: Dark Suspense Novels Rage On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The characters who inhabit Black Lizard books are contemporary losers struggling through scenes set in the sizzling middle of hell on earth. Although that may not spur hordes of readers to rush out to buy one, <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lizard </ORGANIZATION> co-founders <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> report their dark suspense novels nevertheless have become a big hit, with sales approaching $ 1 million this year. They're not worried that fans of traditional mysteries or gothic romances shun harsh Lizard novels such as `` A Ticket to Hell,'' `` The Alcoholics,'' `` Swamp Sister'' or `` A Moment to Prey.'' `` I do n't read mysteries, I do n't know anything about mysteries ... I ca n't read them,'' said <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON>, contending most are poorly written and focus primarily on advancing the plot. Black Lizard books may contain a mystery, but many do n't include a corpse or even a crime, he said. As the editor who selects the <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lizard </ORGANIZATION> lineup, <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> has a clear vision of what fits and what does n't, and he has no intention of trying to attract the fainthearted. These thrillers are `` not just hard-boiled. They're books with a certain psychological edge,'' he said. Many of Black Lizard's readers are young, and <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> speculated they may share the generally nihilistic views presented in the novels Consider this classic Black Lizard example from `` Cassidy's Girl'' by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodis </PERSON>: `` A feeling of vague uneasiness took root inside him and grew and sharpened and became acute He knew he was disappointed because the battle had n't continued. Of course, he told himself, that did n't make sense. But then there were very few elements in his life with <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON> that made sense. And lately, he recalled, there was absolutely nothing that made sense. It was getting worse all the time.'' In Black Lizard's own bibliography, the novels are described as presenting `` distinctive and absolutely authentic -LRB- mostly -RRB- American voices; satirical, maddening, compelling, fascinating.'' According to <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lizard </ORGANIZATION> has become so successful that major publishing companies are trying to imitate the innovations of the small <ORGANIZATION> Creative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> company that has carried the <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lizard </ORGANIZATION> imprint since 1983. That's when <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> was browsing in a <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> bookstore and discovered a stack of <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittington </PERSON> novels, many of them the same `` dark'' 25-cent paperbacks that he loved to read as a kid while hanging out at his <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> neighborhood drugstore. While the books' popularity had plunged in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since the'50s, they remained a strong favorite with the French, who have shown steady appreciation of the `` serie noire'' storyline of such authors as <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Whittington </PERSON> and <PERSON> Goodis </PERSON>. `` It best represents the vision of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that the French like to retain,'' <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> said. `` It's kind of like the Wild West.'' Filmmaker <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Truffaut </PERSON> claimed <PERSON> Goodis </PERSON> as one of his favorites, filming the writer's `` Shoot the Piano Player.'' <PERSON> Goodis </PERSON> also wrote `` Dark Passage,'' and did the screenplay as well for the <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogart-Lauren </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacall </PERSON> film. <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON>'s own `` Port Tropique'' is in pre-production for a movie. He said his friend, best-selling novelist <PERSON> Elmore </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, routinely calls to suggest <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lizard </ORGANIZATION> nab a certain new author or novel. `` It's become a writers' series as well,'' <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> said. But the company's budget remains relatively small and it's impossible for it to lure big names such as <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> And some <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> publishing houses trying to duplicate <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lizard </ORGANIZATION> have landed certain books and authors by paying higher fees. Even so, <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizard </PERSON> founders are confident that by retaining the novels' strong identity it will survive and flourish. `` You can fill it -LRB- a company's booklist -RRB- with a lot of glop, but pretty soon your readership falls away,'' said <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON>. `` I think we're just going to get better at what we do, not necessarily bigger,'' <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> said. Despite Black Lizard's surge in popularity, <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> said he was n't sure what to expect at first: `` I thought it would either catch on right away or we would n't sell more than 10 books. I did n't expect a mediocre reaction.'' They started out printing 5,000 copies for each of their first three books. Today they begin with 10,000 copies each, reprinting when necessary. Their booklist totals 43. Black Lizard is publishing its first hardcovers this spring and bookstore chains such as <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> and Waldenbooks have placed orders. Black Lizard books are easy to spot. In addition to the trademark lizard logo taken from a Peruvian stone rubbing and strategically placed on each cover, most of the novels also feature haunting, lurid cover designs by <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> artist <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirwin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> said they decided to tone down the focus of the novel cover after the first three, making it less violent and graphic yet `` something that can penetrate the psyche. ... It's almost like a dream.'' The covers have become so successful that contrary to the old maxim, some people judge Black Lizard books by their covers and buy them for that reason alone.
