<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Never Die Young'' -LRB- CBS -RRB- _ <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> `` Never Die Young'' is classic <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, which is to say warm, melodic, soothing, thoughtful, reminiscent of `` Sweet Baby James'' _ progressive but just as personal. The LP's title comes from the fine cut: `` Never give up, never slow down, never grow old, never die young.'' Love seems to be in bloom once again in the rock world. Well, sort of. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON> recently turned away from larger issues to tackle the subject in `` Tunnel of Love.'' `` Never Die Young'' is <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s two-cents' worth. It's prettier and more cutting. On the cover of `` Tunnel of Love,'' <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON> leans on a convertible on a beach. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> puts a lone wolf on `` Never Die Young.'' It's the call of the wild. His affinity for the wild life helped destroy his marriage with singer-songwriter <PERSON> Carly </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, and he talks a lot here about troubled relationships. Take `` Valentine's Day,'' which starts as a silly sweet ode to romance: `` Beneath the tide the fishes glide, fin to fin and side to side, for fishy love has now begun, fishy love, finny fun.'' But in later verses, its true nature surfaces: `` Me and you, you and him, him and her, us and them, we keep score, love as war, Valentine's Day.'' `` Runaway Boy'' is a slice of Zydeco that inspires <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> to declare he's cleaning up his act: `` I'm gon na give up believing I was born to run, and stop acting like a man that gets shot from a gun. I'm putting down roots, I want to soak up the sun and stay right here until my days are done.'' `` Sweet Potato Pie'' is the most commercial cut, a happy bounce down a latter-day Tin Pan Alley. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> even rhymes June, moon, spoon and loon. `` Never Die Young'' is tough, pretty, loose, funny _ just about perfect. Luckily for us, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> took his own advice. _ By <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Pontiac'' -LRB- MCA-Curb -RRB- _ <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON> Country singer <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON> looks more like a Pet Shop Boy than an Oak Ridge Boy, so it's no surprise that `` Pontiac'' is slightly off center. The tone is set by the opening song, `` If I Had a Boat,'' wherein <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON> recalls the time <PERSON> Tonto </PERSON> told off the Lone Ranger. It's impossible not to like. Other highlights are the title cut, which could have been writen by <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> in a dark mood; `` <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>,'' with a violent climax that <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON> nearly sneaks past the listener; and three hilarious songs about the art of compromise _ `` Give Back My Heart,'' `` She's No Lady'' and `` She's Hot to Go.'' <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON> includes several graceful bows to traditional <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> as well. The best is `` Walk Through the Bottomland,'' which features <PERSON> Emmylou </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' harmony on the chorus. <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON>, who co-produced, does n't clutter the arrangements. But along with pedal steel and piano, he effectively uses horns and, on the title song, a cello. Altogether, `` Pontiac'' is a most enjoyable ride. _ By <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Wine </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
