<HEAD>Oil Prices Up On Jump in Heating Oil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil futures prices have moved above $ 16 per barrel on the strength of a big jump in heating oil prices that analysts said was prompted by reports of bad weather in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> crude for April delivery settled at $ 16.01 per 42-gallon barrel Monday, up 23 cents from Friday's close. Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale heating oil for March delivery gained 1.46 cents to 47.16 cents per gallon and wholesale unleaded gasoline gained .45 cent to 45.71 cents per gallon. Analysts said several days of bad weather in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and cooler than normal temperatures in the northeastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had touched off the heavy buying in heating oil. Storms reported in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> also prompted some buying among oil companies hedging against a slowdown in production, the analysts said. `` The market is testing to see if we have bargain prices,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said last week's reports speculating about excess production by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, which helped depress crude prices, may have been overblown `` There is still a lot of oil out there, but whether it's a big excess or a little excess is what we're trying to find out,'' he said.
