<HEAD>Saturn Begins Recruiting Workers for Tennessee Assembly Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s newest carmaking division has begun recruiting the first 3,000 factory workers for its <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, assembly plant, <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The Saturn plant will begin production in the summer of 1990 for the 1991 model year. Most workers will be hired in mid-1989, when <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> begins production on pilot models, said <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> representatives will tour <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> facilities around the nation, explaining directly to workers for the first time how <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> will work and what a job there would be like. Saturn already has received a number of resumes, but the push announced Monday is the first real recruitment effort it has made. Under an agreement between <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> workers will get the first 6,000 Saturn jobs available over time, including the initial 3,000. Saturn workers will be covered by a separate labor contract from the national GM-UAW pact. Like Japanese automakers that have hired for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories, including <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION>'s hiring process will be lengthy Potential Saturn workers will go through an assessment process intended to give them an idea of what <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> work will be like and whether they want to do it, while giving <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> an idea of how well the prospective employee works in a team situation, <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> employees will work in teams, instead of performing more traditional auto assembly work that consists of repeating one precise task over and over. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said the Saturn plant probably will run on two shifts. Workers' salaries will amount to 80 percent of <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> hourly workers' base pay, with the 20 percent difference made up in incentive pay linked to such factors such as productivity increases and <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION>'s profitability, <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said. Active or laid-off workers who leave the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> system for <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> automatically give up any recall rights and seniority at <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> plants, she said. But at <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION>, their jobs would be protected during industry slumps because the company will be required to look for ways to cut its inventory that exclude laying off workers, <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said.
