<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has filed a lawsuit seeking at least $ 21 million from <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for allegedly falsifying price information about balloon-type devices used to guide bombs. The suit, originally filed last year by a competitor, was taken over by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> and filed Monday in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. The suit names <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary called <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Loral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which bought the subsidiary last year. `` Goodyear is confident that once the facts in the case are examined objectively, the suit will be found without merit and the charges dropped,'' <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> McClenny </PERSON> said from his <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, office. The case involves two devices called Air Inflatable Retarder Assemblies that are used to slow and guide the flight of MK 500-pound and 1,000-pound bombs dropped from low-flying airplanes. The government charged that <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> misrepresented prices and costs of the labor involved; that the company unlawfully induced a subcontractor to lower its price; and that it failed to disclose substantial price reductions proposed for a subcontractor. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> was the only maker of the devices from 1982 to 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Irvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> entered the competition and filed a $ 100 million antitrust suit in 1986. <PERSON> Irvin </PERSON> allegedly turned up information about fraud against the government that it used in another suit it filed in 1987. That suit was filed on behalf of the government under a `` whistleblower'' law that allows the government to take over a suit. The suit filed Monday asks for at least $ 21 million in damages under the False Claims Act and common law theories. In addition, the government is seeking $ 10,000 for each unspecified false claim. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Loral </ORGANIZATION>, who asked not to be identified, said that those alleged practices would have occurred before <ORGANIZATION> Loral </ORGANIZATION> bought the company and the potential for a lawsuit was known before the purchase. He added, however, that `` Loral is confident the appropriate management practices are in place that are consistent with government procurement practices.''
