<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Script writers and entertainment producers, trying to hammer out a strike-averting contract settlement, called a recess today after a 21-hour bargaining session. The <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> said in a brief statement that negotiators recessed at 7:15 a.m. and agreed to return at noon. Both sides declined to say if an agreement was near, but alliance and union officials earlier expressed pessimism. The old contract for the 9,000 members expired at midnight Monday with no resolution to the union's demands for greater creative control on the set and more money from television residuals. `` It does n't look optimistic,'' said <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> WGA </ORGANIZATION>, which represents about 6,500 writers on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and 2,500 on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. `` The situation is not good,'' agreed <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION>. The writers produce scripts for productions ranging from daytime soap operas and talk shows to prime-time dramas and feature films. A strike would be felt first by daily daytime programs and talk shows, Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said. She said it would take longer for the effects of a walkout to become visible on shows produced in advance that need fewer scripts. Negotiators were still at the bargaining table at 5 a.m. this morning and were expected to wrap up today. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> union members would vote tonight on whether to