<HEAD>Sunflower Seeds More Than A Symbol in Kansas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY STREFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For some <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> farmers, sunflowers have become more than a state symbol. Wild sunflowers have always flourished here _ hence <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>' reputation as the <ORGANIZATION> Sunflower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> _ but now, farmers in the northwest and north central part of the state are making money by growing the tall, green and yellow plants for sale to snack-food processing plants `` We're the newest crop in the state, and the fastest-growing,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Featherstone </PERSON>, one of two <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> men who opened the Ag Dynamics sunflower seed processing plant in <LOCATION> Goodland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, in October 1986. The two sought to locate their plant at <LOCATION> Goodland </LOCATION>, a small farming community near the state's border with <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, because its high altitude, low humidity, long growing season and irrigation are perfect for cultivating the high-quality sunflowers used in snack foods, <PERSON> Featherstone </PERSON> said. Although most of the sunflower processing has been done in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, the prime growing area is shifting southward to <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, officials said. According to an informal survey by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, the total number of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> acres planted in sunflowers increased from about 60,000 acres in 1982 to about 200,000 in 1987. Farmers yield about 2,000 pounds of sunflower seeds an acre. From 1985 to 1987, the number of acres planted in non-oil seeds in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> increased by about 41,000. Sunflower seeds are used to produce oil and bird seed, in addition to snack foods. `` It's not ever going to take over wheat,'' said Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Brownback </PERSON>, `` but it does bring in some money for these people.'' It was n't always that way. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> has been strong in growing basic crops with stable markets, but has lagged behind other states in growing and marketing specialty crops. `` They can grow the stuff but the problem has always been marketing,'' <PERSON> Featherstone </PERSON> said. `` Marketing is more than just taking orders.'' When Ag Dynamics first moved into the <LOCATION> Goodland </LOCATION> area, for example, some farmers were growing sunflowers for use in sunflower oil and bird seed. But growers were reluctant to venture into the snack-food market because they were unfamiliar with the crop and skeptical of its money-making potential. Depressed prices for traditional money-makers, such as corn and wheat, convinced many to take the plunge into the sunflower business. Ag Dynamics helped ease the transition for some by guaranteeing a market their specialty crop. `` We cover his -LRB- the farmer's -RRB- product by selling contracts to roasters on the other end,'' <PERSON> Featherstone </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Brownback </PERSON> cautions that each farmer must decide whether alternative crops such as sunflowers are right for his or her situation. Many established farmers have no incentive to try alternative crops, <PERSON> Brownback </PERSON> said, but smaller farmers with less capital or those with debts receive needed cash when they grow on contract. At the <LOCATION> Goodland </LOCATION> plant, seeds are dehulled, cleaned, sorted and bagged and then shipped out of state to several nut companies, where they are roasted, bagged and distributed, <PERSON> Brownback </PERSON> said. Ag Dynamics sells its sunflower seeds to about 40 nut companies, including Planters. They also export about 25 percent of the crop to other countries, such as <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. For the 1988 crop, they will contract with farmers to grow about 30,000 acres, <PERSON> Featherstone </PERSON> said. Their first year, they contracted for about 350 acres. Improving the field-to-market organization has brightened the future for <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> sunflower growers considerably. Processing plants in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> also are beginning to contract with <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> farmers for the sunflower seeds they use to produce snacks. `` A major portion of the crop is now swinging down into <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Featherstone </PERSON> said. And the quality of the seeds grown in northwest <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> is so good, <PERSON> Brownback </PERSON> said, `` We're getting some people requesting <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> sunflowers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 5-6</NOTE>
