 The stock market stumbled today after vaulting to a new post-crash high on Monday. The Dow Jones industrial average of 30 blue-chip stocks was down 1.33, or 0.06 percent, to 2,070.29 at noon on Wall Street. Analysts had expected to see the market follow through on Monday's advance, but the move failed to materialize in the early going. Some said the morning's activity was highlighted by big investors cashing in their gains. Stocks losing ground outnumbered gainers by 775 to 602 with 461 issues unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> totaled 103.25 million at noon, off from 133.99 million at the same time Monday when dividend plays on utility stocks ignited an early trading burst. `` It's sort of a pause to take profits and see where we go next,'' observed <PERSON> Eldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Grimm </PERSON>, senior vice president for Birr, <ORGANIZATION> Wilson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts said traders found little to inspire them in the economic data released this morning. The government said its chief economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in January, but an upward revision for December eased fears of an imminent recession. Also today, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said construction spending tumbled 2.9 percent in January, the biggest decline in 10 months. But as in the case of the leading index, the drop followed a revised 0.4 percent increase in December. Analysts said the figures were in line with expectations and had little impact on trading. Aside from the economic data, market traders were expected to focus on the latest rash of takeover deals, which helped propel Monday's surge. Among the most active stocks on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> gained 1 -RRB- to 67 ~ following <ORGANIZATION> R.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> offer of $ 73.80-per-share for about 80 percent of the company's outstanding shares <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which has been chasing <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> with a bid of $ 68 per share, said <PERSON> Macy </PERSON>'s offer was `` simply not competitive.'' But other results were mixed. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Roebuck </PERSON> was up \ to 38; <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> was down \ to 45 \, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> was up 1 to 37 -RCB-, <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s was down -LRB- to 7 -RRB-; and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> was up -RRB- to 117 The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all its listed common stocks was down 0.51 to 149.95 at mid-day. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index was up 0.65 to 289.11. On Monday, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 48.41 to 2,071.62, reaching its highest point since the October crash. The run left the Dow average 20 points higher than the previous post-crash peak of 2,051.89 on Jan. 7. Analysts noted that while today's early performance was disappointing, the market appeared firm enough to avoid the kind of slide that followed the January advance. The day after hitting that peak, the Dow plunged 140 points.
