<HEAD>Texas International Suspends Dept Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has suspended payment of interest and principal on subordinated debts totaling $ 155 million. The <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City-based </LOCATION> oil and gas company announced Monday that interest payments on the $ 155 million subordinated debt had become more than the company can handle. Payments on other debt obligations will continue, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON>, director of investor relations for the company. `` Our business environment has simply come to the point where it is presently not in the best interests of either our shareholders or our subordinated debt holders for us to remain current on our subordinated debt as it is currently structured,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kishpaugh </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer. The first payment suspended was a biannual interest payment of $ 869,000 due Monday on the company's 10 percent Second Delayed Convertible Senior Subordinated Notes due Dec. 31, 1993, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said. Principal on those notes is about $ 32 million, he said. The company has about 11 other issues of subordinated notes, he said. `` The problem is we're not generating enough cash flow from our Egyptian assets'' to be able to handle both current debt and move ahead in the company's exploration plans, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said. By the end of 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> had expected crude oil production to be between 3overy on the Khalda concession in the Egyptian western desert, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said. Instead, the concession is producing 20,000 barrels daily, with <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> receiving about 10 percent of that, he said. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said the company plans to meet with creditors and establish a plan to allow it to continue its exploration activities in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and elsewhere.
