<HEAD>Italy's Opposition to 1988 Budget Endangers EEC Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Financial reforms agreed to by leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> two weeks ago appeared threatened Tuesday by <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s refusal to pay its share into the 1988 budget. Sources within the 12-nation Common Market said <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s objections to the budget draft could lead other <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> states to disavow their earlier consent to the reforms `` Once one country begins to question the agreement, all others will want to do the same,'' one official said. The official, who asked to remain anonymous in keeping with established practice, said the problem is likely to be sent to a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> foreign ministers to be held March 5 at <LOCATION> Konstanz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` Of course, we are very disappointed that we have to deal with this problem at this stage,'' said a German official who asked not to be named. `` The whole situation endangers the 1988 budget ... everything is blocked,'' he said. The much-heralded reforms, agreed in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> Feb. 13, were designed to rein in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s skyrocketing farm spending and give the trading bloc a sound financial footing for the next five years. But <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s objections had forced Common Market budget ministers last Wednesday to suspend efforts to adopt the overdue spending plan. In a letter Monday to West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Goria </PERSON> rejected the formula as offending `` the principles'' on which the reforms stand. An official message from <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> Tuesday said <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s contribution to the fund was at least $ 143 million higher than agreed at the summit. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which currently holds the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> presidency, gave <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> until noon Tuesday to change its mind. But the deadline passed and the Italian government remained adamant in opposing the new formula for calculating national contributions to a budget supplement set at 7.6 billion European currency units, or $ 8.2 billion. That amount is needed to bridge the gap between anticipated spending needs totaling the equivalent of $ 54.6 billion and revenue available under current EEC rules.
