 <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> financier <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurwitz </PERSON> has moved to gain control of <ORGANIZATION> KaiserTech </ORGANIZATION>, the world's fifth largest aluminum producer, with an agreement to pay up to $ 230 million for a 32.1 percent voting share. <PERSON> Hurwitz </PERSON>' bid to <ORGANIZATION> KaiserTech </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clore </PERSON> competed with a bid by <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>, a Swiss aluminum business owner. <PERSON> Hurwitz </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Clore </PERSON>, has no experience in the aluminum industry. The announcement Monday said the company would have preferred that the British industrialist's' holdings be sold more broadly. <PERSON> Clore </PERSON> was under intense pressure to sell from creditors. If <PERSON> Clore </PERSON> had n't found a buyer by a Monday deadline, he could have faced default on loans he had obtained using <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON> stock as collateral. After the stock plunged because of the October market crash, lenders wanted repayment. The Oakland-based company's stock rose $ 1.125 a share Monday to close at $ 11.875 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Under the deal, Los Angeles-based <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a company controlled by <PERSON> Hurwitz </PERSON>, agreed to buy from <PERSON> Clore </PERSON> and his lenders 6.2 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> KaiserTech </ORGANIZATION> stock for $ 12 a share. Once <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION> purchases the stock, it has an option to acquire 8.2 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> KaiserTech </ORGANIZATION> convertible preferred stock at $ 13.75 to $ 14 a share. <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION> also must pay $ 8 million to $ 10 million in expenses, the nature of which was undisclosed. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION> is negotiating agreements with other parties to buy an additional 2.8 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> KaiserTech </ORGANIZATION> common stock for $ 12 a share. It was not clear what effect <ORGANIZATION> Maxxam </ORGANIZATION>'s purchase would have immediately on the <ORGANIZATION> KaiserTech </ORGANIZATION> board. All 14 seats are up for election shortly. Included are eight board members appointed by <PERSON> Clore </PERSON>, including <PERSON> Clore </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Pasman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON>'s chief executive officer. The probable changes in <ORGANIZATION> KaiserTech </ORGANIZATION>'s executive suite and boardroom come as the company is rebounding from six straight years of losses. <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON> has sold its chemicals, oil and gas businesses, has slashed debt, and is concentrating on its core aluminum business.
