<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Prices Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar ended mostly lower against major foreign currencies Tuesday after another sluggish trading session in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Gold prices rose. Traders said the dollar came under some mild selling pressure late in the day, possibly because of a slightly worse-than-expected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> leading indicators statistic for January. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the index fell 0.6 percent in January, but the decline was partly offset by a revision in the December index to a 0.3 percent rise from a previously announced 0.2 percent fall. Many dealers discounted the dollar's slight decline Tuesday and said the market remains stagnant. The British pound, meanwhile, was boosted by higher interest rates in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Sterling rose to $ 1.7775 from $ 1.7725 Monday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with late Monday included: 1.6855 West German marks, down from 1.6875; 1.3915 Swiss francs, up from 1.3903; 5.7065 French francs, down from 5.7150; 1.8940 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8945; 1,244.35 Italian lire, up from 1,244.25; 1.2570 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2622. The dollar rose in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, closing at 128.63 Japanese yen, up from Monday's close of 128.12 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was lower at 128.30 yen. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 428.70 a troy ounce, compared with Monday's late bid of $ 425. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was higher at a bid $ 429.50 compared with $ 426 Monday. The metal closed in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> at a bid $ 433.80, up from $ 430.19. Silver bullion prices rose on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 6.29 a troy ounce, compared with $ 6.14 Monday.
