<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-USTrade Bjt   03-01 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Trade, Bjt,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Trade Figures Send Mixed Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Looking at <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade figures for the past year is like looking at a glass of water _ the glass is either half empty or half full, depending on one's perspective. From the Japanese side, the figures show improvement, with exports beginning to decline in volume terms after years of growth that provoked resentment among its trading partners. From the American side, the trade deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> rose again, mainly because the soaring yen inflated the cost of Japanese imports. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, government officials are optimistic that recent trade statistics show a trend toward reducing <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s huge trade surplus. But independent economists are voicing reservations over long-term trade prospects. Referring to the latest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures, a <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> official said the tide is slowly turning and that, although the figures showed the biggest deficit in history, the imbalance with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> actually decreased. `` It depends on whether you look at trade in yen or dollar terms,'' he said. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s exports rose 5.6 percent in dollar terms but fell 8.2 percent in yen terms in the last three months of 1987, compared to a year earlier. At the same time, imports rose in terms of both dollars and yen. `` As for volume, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s imports are growing, with a big increase from the newly industrialized countries and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, though the increase with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was not so large,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. According to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> figures, the trade deficit last year was a record $ 171.2 billion, up from $ 156.2 billion in 1986. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' largest bilateral deficit again was with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ a record $ 59.8 billion, up from $ 58.6 billion in 1986 and $ 49.7 billion in 1985. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Napier </PERSON>, vice president and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> economist with the investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, does see a short-term easing in the trade imbalance, but warns that good figures in the short term may be misleading. `` The first quarter looks good, and we will see a brief lull because Japanese automakers have too much inventory already in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` But I do n't really think the figures for the final quarter of 1987 signal that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus has topped out. There were basically no trends in 1987.'' Barriers keeping <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exporters out of certain Japanese markets, such as highly controversial restrictions on imported beef, citrus fruits and rice, add to the trade imbalance problem and have come under heavy fire from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government. But the most pressing question now may not be barriers or exchange rates, <PERSON> Napier </PERSON> said. `` I think that the yen-dollar rate is no longer a problem for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exporters. More marketing focus is needed in this country, which traditionally has not been a target,'' he said. <PERSON> Napier </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> lags behind <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the newly industrialized countries in expanding exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> because of a lack of distribution facilities, an insufficient sales force and scanty product representation. `` It was interesting to hear that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Steel would be exporting again, but that they chose <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as their market,'' he said. The official at the Japanese trade ministry agreed. `` Success depends on exporters' efforts,'' he said. `` Exporters in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> now have the chance to compete. Japanese consumers are changing and there are more and more foreign products for sale in supermarkets here. `` Domestic demand for foreign goods is increasing, so now is the time for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> to try to expand in the Japanese market. Exporters should act immediately to take advantage of developments here,'' he added. `` As for the future prospects of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, I think that with the yen-dollar rate our imports will continue to steadily increase.'' <PERSON> Napier </PERSON> also offers some comfort to Americans wondering if the trade imbalance with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will ever end. `` The marketing focus is starting to change, with more attention being given to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` It may take awhile, but this will eventually have an impact.''
</TEXT>
