<TEXT>
 The dollar fell marginally against most key currencies Tuesday, reflecting what dealers called a narrow trading range that has emerged over the past several days. Gold prices rose overseas but were mixed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. As of 4 p.m. EST, <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted gold at $ 430.45 a troy ounce, down 15 cents from the price late Monday. Currency dealers said there was little news to influence the behavior of the dollar. They said a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report on the index of leading indicators, an important economic barometer, failed to convey a definite trend. The department said the index fell 0.6 percent in January but it revised the December figure from a 0.2 percent drop to a 0.3 percent increase. That revision snapped a string of three straight monthly declines, which has often signaled an impending recession. `` We need something more specific to set the market one way or another,'' said <PERSON> Zlatko </PERSON> <PERSON> Glamuzina </PERSON>, chief currency dealer at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> branch of the Italian bank <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> di </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sicilia </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorsch </PERSON>, senior money market economist at <ORGANIZATION> LNS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said `` there appears to be very little impetus for traders to move out of the dollar's range, at least in the near term.'' By contrast, he said, currencies such as the British pound and Canadian dollar seemed to be appreciating because of relatively high interest rates in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. `` We're seeing a lot of deflation in commodity markets and weakness in gold prices, which supports the idea that global interest rates will be steady to lower,'' <PERSON> Dorsch </PERSON> said. `` So international money managers are searching for higher yields.'' The dollar rose in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, closing at 128.63 Japanese yen, up from the Monday close of 128.12 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was lower at 128.30 yen. By the time trading concluded in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar was trading at 128.32 yen, marginally higher than 128.24 rate late Monday. The British pound rose to $ 1.7775 from $ 1.7725 Monday on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, sterling was quoted at $ 1.7766, more than the $ 1.7742 quoted late Monday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> compared with late Monday levels included: 1.6864 West German marks, down from 1.6874; 1.3916 Swiss francs, down from 1.3931; 1.2578 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2592; 5.7100 French francs, down from 5.7155; 1,243.25 Italian lire, up from 1,243. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with late Monday included: 1.6855 West German marks, down from 1.6875; 1.3915 Swiss francs, up from 1.3903; 5.7065 French francs, down from 5.7150; 1.8940 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8945; 1,244.35 Italian lire, up from 1,244.25; 1.2570 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2622. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 428.70 a troy ounce, compared with $ 425 late Monday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold rose to $ 429.50 vs. $ 426, and in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> gold closed at $ 433.80 vs. $ 430.19. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York