<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, target of a hostile $ 2.12 billion takeover attempt by <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Decker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday it was taking steps to sweeten the cash portion of a recapitalization designed to foil the bid. The company said it had begun talks with unidentified third parties regarding the possible sale of debt securities as a means of increasing the cash part of the recapitalization, which would pay shareholders $ 1.9 billion plus give them a stake in the recapitalized company. A recapitalization, in which a company restructures its amount of debt and equity, is used often to thwart unwelcome takeovers. The strategy usually plunges a company into debt, making it less attractive as an acquisition. Under the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> recapitalization plan, which would raise the company's long-term debt from $ 412 million to $ 2.3 billion, stockholders would receive $ 59 in cash, $ 5 worth of high-yielding debt securities and one new share of stock in the recapitalized company for each share of old stock. The company's announcement Tuesday did not elaborate on how much it intended to raise the cash portion of the recapitalization but said there was no assurance that any change would be made in the existing proposal. In composite <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> stock rose 12 -LCB- cents a share to $ 68.62 -LCB-. Black and <PERSON> Decker </PERSON> stock rose 62 -LCB- cents a share to $ 19.12 -LCB-. Black & amp; <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>, a tool and appliance maker 