<HEAD>Stocks Slip After Struggling To Hold Gains</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES M. KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market slipped off its post-crash peak Tuesday but showed enough spunk to hold most of its recent gains. The Dow Jones industrial average of 30 stocks bounced off its lows late in the day, closing down 1.16 points, or a scant 0.06 percent, at 2,070.46. With an hour to go, the blue-chip average had been down more than 13 points, but traders took the opportunity to buy stocks, pushing the Dow near Monday's close of 2,071.62, its high-water mark since the Oct. 19 collapse. Stocks declining in price outpaced gainers by 7 to 6 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 811 issues declining, 696 gaining and 457 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 199.99 million shares, against 236.05 million in the previous session. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index dipped 0.28 to 150.18. The market's lackluster numbers belied its resilience, some analysts said. They noted that the market's previous post-crash high, reached on Jan. 7, was followed the next day by a drop of more than 140 points. The relative firmness of prices Tuesday suggested to some that the market had finally found its sealegs. `` The market had every reason to go down and it did n't,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, a technical analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Traders are no longer afraid of a crash; they're afraid of missing a buying opportunity,'' said <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>. Others were not so sure. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Johson </PERSON>, chief investment officer for <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, characterized the market as `` almost lifeless,'' adding that uncertainty about the economy was still a drag on trading. A batch of government statistics released Tuesday failed to satisfy the market's curiosity about the economy's health. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said its chief economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in January, but the December reading for the Index of Leading Economic Indicators was revised from a 0.2 percent drop to a 0.3 percent gain. The government also said construction spending tumbled 2.9 percent in January, the biggest decline in 10 months. But as was the case with the leading index, the drop followed a revised 0.4 percent increase in December. `` It was a little frustrating,'' said <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. `` We had hoped to resolve some of the uncertainty -LRB- about the economy -RRB- and we did n't.'' `` The only conclusion is ... we'll miss a recession -LRB- in 1988 -RRB-, but not by much,'' he said. Aside from the economic data, issues swept up in the latest rash of takeover deals dominated interest as they had Monday when the Dow jumped more than 48 points. Among the most active stocks on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> gained 1 \ to a new high of 67 -RCB- following <ORGANIZATION> R.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> offer of $ 73.80 a share for about 80 percent of the company's outstanding shares <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stevens </ORGANIZATION>, which received a revised buyout offer from a management group and said other parties had expressed interest in the company, jumped 6 \ to 54 -LCB-, also a new high Other results were mixed. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Roebuck </PERSON> was up -LCB- to 38 \; <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </