<HEAD>Wheat Futures Prices Slip Amid USDA Auction Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Wheat futures prices slipped substantially lower Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> as the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> launched a new series of auctions aimed at reducing government stockpiles of surplus wheat. On other markets, other grains and soybeans ended mostly lower; energy futures retreated; most livestock and meat futures advanced; precious metals were mixed; and stock-index futures were higher.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly auctions of suplus wheat, begun in November, have gradually lost steam. So on Tuesday the agency launched a new series of sales to be held three times a week. The agency has set targets of 10 million bushels for each of the new auctions during the first two weeks, which creates the potential for adding 30 million bushels a week to the open market. The old weekly auctions usually had targets of 25 million bushels. Sales in recent weeks had fallen well short of that goal, however, with less than 16 million bushels sold last Friday. Traders fear the new auctions, which divide the sales by regions of the country, will be more successful and depress cash prices by adding to available supplies of wheat, analysts said. `` The possibility of selling 10 milllion bushels the first time out is probably going to be a little tough,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gidel </PERSON> of Chicago-based G.H. <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` But it's the fact that they're coming right back tomorrow, then on Friday again, that has the market a little on edge. However, analyst <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinton </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Agri-Visor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, said the new auctions probably would have little long-term impact on futures prices. <PERSON> Quinton </PERSON> attributed Tuesday's wheat losses of up to 5 cents a bushel to profit-taking by speculators. Results from Tuesday's auction will likely be released on Wednesday. Wheat settled 4 -LCB- cents to 5 cents lower with the contract for delivery in March at $ 3.11 a bushel; corn was unchanged to -RCB- cent lower with March at $ 2.03 -RCB- a bushel; oats were unchanged to -LCB- cent higher with March at $ 1.94 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1 -LCB- cents higher with March at $ 6.35 a bushel. Energy futures prices, particularly for refined products, fell sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where analysts said bulls and bears have been waging a technical tug-of-war. `` This market seems to be moving briskly within a range, which is what it probably will continue to do before it decides which way it wants to go,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. West Texas Intermediate crude oil traded as much as .46 cent lower, but settled .11 cent to .29 cent lower with April at $ 15.72 a barrel; heating oil was .82 cent to 1.15 cents lower with April at 43.47 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .93 cent to 1.10 cents lower with April at 45.29 cents a gallon Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Cattle futures moved higher in mostly technical trading, analysts said. Hog futures advanced on bargain buying after Monday's sharp decline, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Linnco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Live cattle were unchanged to .52 cent higher with April at 71.95 a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .85 cent higher with March at 80.42 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .40 cent higher with April at 43.47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were unchanged to .42 cent lower with March at 51.60 cents a pound. Gold moved slightly higher while silver futures retreated a bit on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Gold for April delivery sank to $ 425 a troy ounce during the session, but rebounded to settle at $ 432.40. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, vice president of Elders' precious metals divison, noted that gold had touched $ 425 on Monday as well, and predicted it would bounce off that level once more before falling to $ 400 a troy ounce in the next three or four weeks. Silver drifted lower in featureless trading, he said. Gold settled 50 cents to 60 cents higher with April at $ 432.40 a troy ounce; silver was 1.7 cents to 2 cents lower with March at $ 6.222 a troy ounce. Stock-index futures inched higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for March delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index setttled .35 point higher at 267.65. The underlying spot index was .59 point lower at 267.23.
