<FIRST>u f AM-EconomyRdp     03-01 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy Rdp,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reports Paint Confusing Picture Of Economy's Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Government reports Tuesday painted a confusing picture about the health of the economy and led to indecision in the financial markets. The government said its chief barometer of future economic activity fell again in January, although an upward revision in December eased fears that the nation was headed for a recession. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 1.16 points to 2,070.46. It was equally quiet in the bond market, where the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year bond fell a slim -LRB- point. The dollar was narrowly mixed. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Index of Leading Economic Indicators dropped 0.6 percent in January. Analysts discounted the sharp decline and instead focused on a revision that changed the index's showing in December from a 0.2 percent decline to a 0.3 percent increase The leading index has taken on added importance since last Oct. 19, when stock prices plunged a record 508 points, eclipsing the 1929 market crash that preceded the Great Depression. The upward revision for December broke a string of three consecutive monthly declines, which has often in the past been the signal of an impending recession. The index had fallen 0.1 percent in October and 1.1 percent in November. Separately, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said construction spending fell 2.9 percent in January, the biggest decline in 10 months, reflecting widespread weakness in all sectors of the building industry. Economists said the decline was bigger than expected and will likely mean that construction will be a drag on overall economic growth in the first quarter of 1988. `` What was surprising about the figures was how widespread and pervasive the weakness was. Virtually every category from housing to industrial to hotels and motels did poorly in January,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Economists said the December revision in the leading index and other positive signs provided evidence that the country is suffering few adverse effects from the market turmoil <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON> said it showed that `` this is a no-recession year for the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. economy.'' Since it was created in 1948, the leading index has fallen three or more months during an expansion on 12 different occasions. On eight of those instances, a recession did follow. But four times the index gave a false signal of a downturn and the recovery kept going, although at a slower pace. Analysts said the index is indeed sending a signal of slower growth for the first half of 1988, but they predicted that rising export sales would be enough to offset expected weakness in consumer spending and construction. The economy, as measured by the gross national product, raced ahead at a 4.5 percent rate in the final three months of 1987, but the bulk of that increase came from a buildup of unsold products. Economists predict that production cutbacks will slash growth to a rate of 1 percent or less in the first three months of the year. For 1988 as a whole, many economists are forecasting growth of around 2 percent, just about half the 3.9 percent GNP increase registered last year. Analysts said various business barometers have eased their fears of an end to the current recovery. `` Industrial production and export sales are still rising, orders and employment continue to grow and the stock market is regaining its balance,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahn </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` Absent any policy blunders by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> or the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, I anticipate a strong second half.''
</TEXT>
