<FIRST>u f AM-WritersTalks 1stLd-Writethru f0169 03-01 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Writers Talks, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0169,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outlook for Writers Settlement Remains Bleak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with talks ending, union saying
management trying to `force' strike, picking up 7th graf pvs,
`First to...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A walkout by 9,000 movie and television script writers seemed likely Tuesday as last-ditch contract talks ended with major issues unresolved and the union saying the producers' last offer appeared designed `` to force a strike.'' Negotiators for the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> met for just two hours before calling it quits Tuesday afternoon. The brief meeting followed a marathon, 21-hour session that lasted until 7:15 a.m. Tuesday and made progress on `` 25 to 30 lesser issues,'' said <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, spokesman for the producers. But the two sides remained far apart on the three major stumbling blocks _ a `` creative rights'' issue that would give original writers more control over the product, higher residual payments when programs are distributed in foreign markets, and a revision of residuals for domestic syndication in the stagnant market for one-hour programs. Both <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> and union spokeswoman <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> confirmed there was no significant movement on those issues in the afternoon session. `` It -LRB- the producers' final offer -RRB- appears to be a company-generated package designed to force a strike,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said. She said the union will study the proposal but declined to say if union leaders would recommend that it be rejected until it is presented to members. The union's 6,500 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> members were to vote Tuesday night on the latest proposal from management, while the 2,500 <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> members are to vote Wednesday afternoon. Results from both votes are to be released Wednesday evening, and a strike could come as early as Thursday if the producers' offer is rejected The union's old contract expired at 12:01 a.m. Tuesday. First to feel the impact of a walkout would be daily daytime TV programs and talk shows that have a short lead time for scripts. The effects on prime-time programs and feature films would n't be visible unless a strike was protracted. For producers, the key issue has been obtaining relief on the payment of residuals for syndication of one-hour television programs. The market for such programs has dried up significantly, producers say. They are asking the writers to adopt a revised residual plan similar to one already approved by directors. Under that plan, writers would 50 percent of the normal residuals if a program is put out in only limited syndication. If it is later put out in full national syndication, they get another 100 percent, making it possible for them to receive 150 percent of their normal payments. On the creative-rights issue, the union is seeking to get original writers the power to do the first rewrite of any material, plus the right to be on the set when the program is produced. The producers say such issues must be negotiated individually. On foreign residuals, the union claims writers have n't had a change in their payment schedule in 17 years. That schedule now is based on a single lump sum payment and varies widely based on individual negotiations. The entertainment arm of the writers' union, which has a reputation as one of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s most militant, last went on strike three years ago. That walkout lasted for two weeks before writers voted to accept essentially the same terms they had rejected earlier. The median annual income for writers is $ 40,000, but about half of the <ORGANIZATION> WGA </ORGANIZATION>'s members are unemployed at any given time, the union says.
