<FIRST>r f BC-SouthKorea-Currency     03-01 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-South Korea-Currency,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Traders' Group Demands Slower Korean Currency Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A major foreign trade group asked the government Wednesday to slow the South Korean currency's appreciation against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar In a report to the government, the <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said the recent sharp rise of the won against the dollar could lead to a series of collapses among exporting firms. A stronger won _ and conversely, a weaker dollar _ raises the costs of Korean products in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a major export market. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been pressuring <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to revalue its currency at a faster pace to help reduce the nation's growing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade surplus, which soared to $ 9.5 billion last year. The association said if the won's value rises 10 percent against the dollar, the average export profitability of South Korean-made products would fall by 3.7 percent. The won has appreciated by 4.13 percent against the dollar so far this year, accounting for about half the range registered for all of 1987. As of Wednesday, the won was quoted at 760.90 to the dollar, down 31.30 won from year-end 1987. If the won continues rising at that pace, its appreciation rate for all of this year could surpass 24 percent, the association said.
